# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: gcp-vertex-ai
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p01] In machine learning, a **neural network** (**NN**) or **neural net**, is a computational model inspired by the structure and functions of biological neural networks.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p01] A neural network consists of connected units or nodes called *artificial neurons*, which loosely model the neurons in the brain.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p01] Artificial neuron models that mimic biological neurons more closely have also been recently investigated and shown to significantly improve performance.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p01] These are connected by *edges*, which model the synapses in the brain.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p01] Each artificial neuron receives signals from connected neurons, then processes them and sends a signal to other connected neurons.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p01] The "signal" is a real number, and the output of each neuron is computed by some non-linear function of the totality of its inputs, called the *activation function*.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p01] The strength of the signal at each connection is determined by a *weight*, which adjusts as part of the training process.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p01] Groups of neurons are aggregated into layers.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p01] Each layer performs a transformation on its inputs.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p01] Signals travel from the first layer (the *input layer*) to the last layer (the *output layer*), typically passing through multiple intermediate layers (*hidden layers*).
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p01] A network is typically called a deep neural network if it has at least two hidden layers.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p01] Deep neural networks are capable of learning sophisticated hierarchical representations.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p01] Training neural networks is a compute-intensive process, accelerated by the use of graphics processing units (GPUs), and large datasets.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p01] Architectural innovations such as convolutional neural networks (CNNs) significantly improved performance in computer vision tasks, while recurrent neural networks (RNNs) enabled modeling of sequential data such as speech and time-series information.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p01] Transformer architectures introduced attention mechanisms that allow neural networks to model long-range dependencies in data and have the basis of large language models.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p01] Artificial neural networks are used for a myriad of tasks including chatbots, large-scale text, image, and video generation, and robotics.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p01] The starfish match with a ringed texture and a star outline, whereas most sea urchins match with a striped texture and oval shape.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p01] However, the instance of a ring textured sea urchin creates a weakly weighted association between them.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p01] The network correctly detects the starfish.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p01] However, the weakly weighted association between ringed texture and sea urchin also confers a weak signal to the latter from one of two intermediate nodes.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p01] In addition, a shell that was not included in the training gives a weak signal for the oval shape, also resulting in a weak signal for the sea urchin output.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p01] In reality, textures and outlines would not be represented by single nodes, but rather by associated weight patterns of multiple nodes.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p01] Deep neural networks are based on statistics developed over 200 years ago.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p01] The simplest kind of feedforward neural network (FNN) is a linear network, which consists of a single layer of output nodes with linear activation functions; the inputs are fed directly to the outputs via weights.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p01] The sum of the products of the weights and the inputs is calculated at each node.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p01] The mean squared errors between these calculated outputs and the given target values are minimized by adjusting to the weights.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p01] This technique is the method of least squares or linear regression.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p01] It was used to find a rough linear fit to a set of points by Legendre (1805) and Gauss (1795) for the prediction of planetary movement.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p01] Computers are based on John von Neumann's model.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p01] They execute explicit lists of instructions with access to memory to record their changing state.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p01] Neural networks instead originated from efforts to model information processing in biological systems via connectionism.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p01] Unlike the von Neumann model, connectionist computing does not separate memory and processing.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p01] Warren McCulloch and Walter Pitts (1943) considered a non-learning computational model for neural networks.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p01] This model paved the way for research to split into one branch focused on biological processes and another focused on artificial intelligence.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p01] McCulloch and Pitts also developed mathematical models of artificial neurons capable of representing logical functions.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p01] Hebb proposed a learning hypothesis based on neural plasticity that became known as Hebbian learning.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p01] It was used in many early neural network experiments, such as Rosenblatt's perceptron and the Hopfield network.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p01] Farley and Clark (1954) used computational machines to simulate a Hebbian network.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p01] Other neural networks computational machines were created by Rochester, Holland, Habit and Duda (1956).
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p01] In 1958, psychologist Frank Rosenblatt described the perceptron, one of the first implemented neural networks, funded by the United States Office of Naval Research.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p01] Joseph (1960) mentioned an earlier perceptron-like device by B.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p01] The first perceptrons did not have adaptive hidden units.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p01] However, Joseph (1960) discussed multilayer that did.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p01] Rosenblatt (1962) cited and adopted these ideas, crediting work by H.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p01] However, these early efforts did not lead to a working learning algorithm for hidden units, i.e., deep learning.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p01] The perceptron raised public excitement in neural networks, causing the US government to drastically increase funding.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p01] This contributed to "the Golden Age of AI", fueled by the optimistic claims made by computer scientists regarding the ability of perceptrons to emulate human intelligence.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p01] Artificial neural networks were identified as a promising direction for artificial intelligence research in the 1955 proposal for the Dartmouth Summer Research Project on Artificial Intelligence.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p01] Neural network models initially faced major limitations.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p01] Hardware constraints limited network size and training efficiency, while theoretical understanding of learning algorithms remained incomplete.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p01] Many models used single-layer perceptrons, which were restricted to solving linearly separable problems.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p01] These limitations were highlighted in the book *Perceptrons* by Marvin Minsky and Seymour Papert, which deflated interest during the late 1960s and 1970s.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p01] Fundamental research was conducted on NNs in the 1960s and 1970s.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p01] The first working deep learning algorithm was the group method of data handling, a method to train arbitrarily deep neural networks, published by Alexey Ivakhnenko and Valentin Lapa in the Soviet Union (1965).
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p01] They regarded it as a form of polynomial regression, generalizing Rosenblatt's perceptron.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p01] A 1971 paper described a deep network with eight layers trained by this method, training layer by layer via regression analysis.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p01] Superfluous hidden units were pruned using a separate validation set.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p01] The activation functions of the nodes were Kolmogorov-Gabor polynomials, the first deep networks with multiplicative units or "gates".
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p01] The first deep learning multilayer perceptron (MLP) trained by stochastic gradient descent was published in 1967 by Shun'ichi Amari.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p01] In computer experiments conducted by Amari's student S.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p01] Saito, a five layer MLP with two modifiable layers learned internal representations to classify non-linearily separable pattern classes.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p01] Subsequent developments in hardware and hyperparameter tuning made end-to-end stochastic gradient descent the dominant technique for reducing loss (error).
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p01] In 1969, Kunihiko Fukushima introduced the ReLU (rectified linear unit) activation function.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p01] RelLU is the most common activation function.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p01] Nevertheless, research stagnated in the United States after Minsky and Papert (1969), who emphasized that perceptrons were incapable of processing the exclusive-or circuit.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p01] However, this insight was irrelevant for the deep networks of Ivakhnenko (1965) and Amari (1967).
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p01] In 1976, transfer learning was introduced.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p01] Interest in neural networks revived during the 1980s because of the novel backpropagation algorithm, which allowed multi-layer neural networks to be trained efficiently by propagating error gradients backward (from output back to input) through network layers.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p01] Backpropagation is an efficient application of the chain rule derived by Gottfried Wilhelm Leibniz in 1673 to networks of differentiable nodes.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p01] The terminology "back-propagating errors" was introduced in 1962 by Rosenblatt, but he did not describe how to implement this.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p01] Kelley developed a precursor of backpropagation in 1960 in the context of control theory.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p01] In 1970, Seppo Linnainmaa published the modern form of backpropagation in his master's thesis (1970).
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p01] Ostrovski et al. republished it in 1971.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p01] Paul Werbos applied backpropagation to neural networks in 1982 (his 1974 PhD thesis, reprinted in a 1994 book, did not describe the algorithm).
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p01] Rumelhart, et al., popularized backpropagation but did not cite the original work.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p01] Deep learning architectures for convolutional neural networks (CNNs) with convolutional layers and downsampling layers and weight replication began with the neocognitron introduced by Kunihiko Fukushima in 1979.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p01] Fukushima's CNN architecture also introduced max pooling, a popular downsampling procedure for CNNs.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p01] CNNs have become an essential tool for computer vision.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p01] The time delay neural network (TDNN) was introduced in 1987 by Alex Waibel to apply CNNs to phoneme recognition.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p01] It used convolutions, weight sharing, and backpropagation.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p01] In 1988, Wei Zhang applied a backpropagation-trained CNN to recognizing individual letters.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p01] In 1989, Yann LeCun et al. created a CNN called LeNet for recognizing handwritten ZIP codes on mail.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p01] In 1990, Wei Zhang implemented a CNN on optical computing hardware.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p01] In 1991, a CNN was applied to medical image object segmentation and breast cancer detection in mammograms.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p01] LeNet-5 (1998), a 7-level CNN by Yann LeCun et al. that classifies hand-written digits, was applied by banks to recognize numbers on checks digitized in 32×32 pixel images.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p01] From 1988 onward, the use of neural networks transformed the field of protein structure prediction, in particular when the first cascading networks were trained on *profiles* (matrices) produced by multiple sequence alignments.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p01] One source of RNN was statistical mechanics.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p01] In 1972, Shun'ichi Amari proposed to modify the weights of an Ising model by Hebbian learning rule as a model of associative memory, adding in learning.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p01] This was popularized as the Hopfield network by John Hopfield (1982).
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p01] The word "recurrent" is used to describe loop-like structures in anatomy.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p01] In 1901, Cajal observed "recurrent semicircles" in the cerebellar cortex.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p01] Hebb considered "reverberating circuit" as an explanation for short-term memory.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p01] The McCulloch and Pitts paper (1943) considered neural networks that contain cycles, and noted that the current activity of such networks can be affected by activity indefinitely far in the past.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p01] In 1982 Crossbar Adaptive Array, a recurrent neural network with an array architecture (rather than a multilayer perceptron architecture), used direct recurrent connections from the output to the supervisor (teaching) inputs.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p01] In addition to computing actions (decisions), it computed internal state evaluations (emotions) of consequence situations.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p01] Eliminating the external supervisor, it introduced the self-learning method in neural networks.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p01] In cognitive psychology, the *American Psychologist* journal in the early 1980s debated the relation between cognition and emotion.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p01] Social psychologist Robert Zajonc in 1980 stated that emotion is computed first and is independent from cognition, while Richard Lazarus in 1982 stated that cognition is computed first and is inseparable from emotion.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p01] It was an example of a debate where an RNN contributed to an issue and also addressed cognitive psychology.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p01] The Jordan network (1986) and the Elman network (1990) applied RNN to study cognitive psychology.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p01] In the 1980s, backpropagation did not work well for deep RNNs.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p01] In 1991, Jürgen Schmidhuber proposed the "neural sequence chunker" or "neural history compressor" which introduced self-supervised pre-training (the "P" in ChatGPT) and neural knowledge distillation.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p01] In 1993, a neural history compressor system solved a "Very Deep Learning" task that required more than 1000 layers in an RNN unfolded in time.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p01] In 1991, Sepp Hochreiter's diploma thesis identified and analyzed the vanishing gradient problem and proposed recurrent residual connections to solve it.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p01] He and Schmidhuber introduced long short-term memory (LSTM), which set accuracy records in multiple application domains.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p01] This was not the ultimate version of LSTM, which required the forget gate, and was introduced in 1999.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p01] It became the default choice for RNN architecture.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p01] During 1985–1995, inspired by statistical mechanics, several architectures and methods were developed by Terry Sejnowski, Peter Dayan, Geoffrey Hinton, and others, including the Boltzmann machine, restricted Boltzmann machine, Helmholtz machine, and the wake-sleep algorithm.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p01] These were designed for unsupervised learning of deep generative models.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p01] Between 2009 and 2012, NNs began winning prizes in image recognition contests, approaching human performance on various tasks, initially in pattern recognition and handwriting recognition.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p01] In 2011, *DanNet,* a CNN by Dan Ciresan, Ueli Meier, Jonathan Masci, Luca Maria Gambardella, and Schmidhuber achieved for the first time superhuman performance in a visual pattern recognition contest, outperforming traditional methods by a factor of 3.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p01] They also showed how max-pooling CNNs on GPU improved performance.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p01] In October 2012, AlexNet by Alex Krizhevsky, Ilya Sutskever, and Hinton won the large-scale ImageNet competition by a significant margin over shallow machine learning methods.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p01] Further incremental improvements included the VGG-16 network by Karen Simonyan and Andrew Zisserman and Google's Inceptionv3.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p01] In 2012, Ng and Dean created a network that learned to recognize higher-level concepts, such as cats, from training only on unlabeled images.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p01] Unsupervised pre-training and increased computing power from GPUs and distributed computing allowed the use of larger networks, particularly in image and visual recognition problems, which became known as "deep learning".
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p01] Radial basis function and wavelet networks were introduced in 2013.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p01] These can be shown to offer best approximation properties and have been applied in nonlinear system identification and classification applications.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p01] Generative adversarial networks (GANs) (Ian Goodfellow et al., 2014) became state of the art in generative modeling from 2014–2018.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p01] GAN was originally published in 1991 by Schmidhuber, who called it "artificial curiosity": two neural networks contest with each other in the form of a zero-sum game, where one network's gain is the other network's loss.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p01] The first network is a generative model that models a probability distribution over output patterns.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p01] The second network learns by gradient descent to predict the reactions of the environment to these patterns.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p01] Excellent image quality was achieved by Nvidia's StyleGAN (2018) based on the Progressive GAN by Tero Karras et al.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p01] Here, the GAN generator is grown from small to large scale in a pyramidal fashion.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p01] Image generation by GAN reached popular success, and provoked discussions concerning deepfakes.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p01] Diffusion models (2015) eclipsed GANs in generative modeling thereafter, with systems such as DALL·E 2 (2022) and Stable Diffusion (2022).
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p01] In 2014, the state of the art was training "[a] very deep neural network" with 20 to 30 layers.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p01] Stacking too many layers led to a steep reduction in training accuracy, known as the "degradation" problem.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p01] In 2015, training very deep networks advanced with the highway network, published in May, and the residual neural network (ResNet) in December.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p01] ResNet behaves like an open-gated Highway Net.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p01] During the 2010s, the seq2seq model was developed, and attention mechanisms were added.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p01] This led to the modern transformer architecture in 2017 in "Attention Is All You Need".
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p01] It requires computation time that is quadratic in the size of the context window.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p01] Schmidhuber's fast weight controller (1992) scales linearly and was later shown to be equivalent to the unnormalized linear transformer.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p01] Transformers have increasingly become the model of choice for natural language processing.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p01] Many modern large language models such as GPT, Gemini, Grok, DeepSeek, and Qwen use this architecture.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p01] NNs began as an attempt to replicate the architecture of the brain in the digital realm.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p01] NNs immediately showed promise for handling non-linear relationships, but encountered obstacles.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p01] Models soon reoriented to applying mathematical insights to improve empirical results, at the expense of biological fidelity.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p01] NNs are composed of digital neurons, conceptually derived from biological neurons.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p01] Each neuron has one or more numerical inputs and produces a single numerical output.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p01] An input (e.g., an image) is typically parceled across the set of input neurons (each getting a piece of the image).
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p01] Each neuron's inputs, weighted by the weights of the connections from each of those inputs are summed.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p01] A bias term is added to this sum.) The result is then passed through a nonlinear activation function to produce the neuron's output.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p01] Small enough outputs may be zeroed out (ignored).
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p01] NNs connect neurons to each other, using the output of some neurons as the input of others, akin to biological axon-synapse-dendrite connections.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p01] The network forms a directed, weighted graph.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p01] The weights apply to both the graph's the nodes and edges.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p01] Nodes are arranged in layers, with the bottom layers directly addressing raw data, while the top layers reveal the final results.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p01] Intermediate layers gradually increase the level of abstraction, so what began as for example, pixels in an image, gradually resolves into things such as object boundaries, and then into real-world objects such as letters and faces.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p01] Single layer and unlayered networks are also used.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p01] Multiple connection patterns have been used.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p01] Traditionally, they are *fully connected*, with every neuron in one layer connecting to every neuron in the next layer.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p01] However, in convolutional neural networks, some layers are *convolutional,* meaning each neuron in one layer is connected to a subset of neurons in the previous layer, such as those representing one section of an image.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p01] In most neural networks, the outputs of the neurons in one layer are connected only to neurons in the immediately following layer (directed acyclic graph), meaning information only flows forward from one layer to the next.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p01] These are known as feedforward networks.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p01] In contrast, networks that allow connections between neurons in the same or previous layers are known as recurrent networks.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p01] Training/learning involves adjusting the weights of the network to improve the accuracy of the result.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p01] NNs typically require vast numbers of sample inputs (far more than biological brains) to achieve a given level of function.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p01] This is done by minimizing the observed errors among sample observations.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p01] Training takes place before a network is deployed, and (unlike brains) does not continue thereafter.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p01] Instead, the network may be retrained from scratch as more sample data becomes available.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p01] Empirical risk minimization adjusts node and link weights to minimize the difference (empirical risk), between the predicted output and the known values in the training samples.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p01] A defined loss function measures the degree of error.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p01] Backpropagation spreads the error (adjusts the weights) from the output nodes across the network to the input nodes.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p01] The intent is to allow the network to process data that is not included in the training samples.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p01] As long as the value of the loss function (its cost) continues to decline, the network is continuing to improve.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p01] The function typically produces a statistic whose value is only approximate.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p01] When the cost is low, the difference between the output (*e.g.* almost certainly a cat) and the correct answer (a cat) is small.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p01] Most learning models can be viewed as a straightforward application of optimization theory and statistical estimation.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p01] Learning typically ends when additional observations do not usefully reduce the cost.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p01] The cost typically approaches, but does not reach, 0.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p01] If no feasible amount of sample data yields a low cost, training is labeled a failure.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p01] While it is possible to assess a loss function ad hoc, typically it must exhibit desirable properties such as convexity, differentiability, and robustness.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p01] In a probabilistic model, the model's posterior probability can be used as an inverse cost (higher values are better).
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p01] Backpropagation is a method used to adjust the connection weights to compensate for errors found during learning.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p01] The error amount is essentially divided among the connections.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p01] Technically, backpropagation calculates the gradient (the derivative) of the loss function associated with a given state with respect to the weights.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p01] The weight updates can be done via stochastic gradient descent or other methods, such as *extreme learning machines*, "no-prop" networks, training without backtracking, "weightless" networks, and non-connectionist neural networks.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p01] A hyperparameter is a parameter defining any configurable part of the network and learning process whose value is set prior to training.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p01] Examples of hyperparameters include learning rate, sample batch size, number of nodes and layers, etc .
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p01] The performance of a neural network is strongly influenced by hyperparameter choices, and thus may be adjusted during training (typically between training runs), a process called hyperparameter tuning or hyperparameter optimization.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p01] The learning rate defines the size of the corrective steps that the model takes to adjust for errors in each observation.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p01] A high learning rate shortens training time, but with lower ultimate accuracy, while a lower learning rate takes longer, but with the potential for greater accuracy.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p01] Optimizations such as quickprop are primarily aimed at accelerating learning.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p01] In order to avoid oscillations such as connection weights that cycle between high and low values, and to improve the rate of convergence, refinements use an adaptive learning rate that increases or decreases as appropriate.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p01] The concept of momentum allows the balance between the gradient and the previous change to be weighted such that the weight adjustment depends to some degree on the previous change.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p01] A momentum close to 0 emphasizes the gradient, while a value close to 1 emphasizes the last change.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p01] Machine learning has involved a variety of approaches to training models, including supervised learning, unsupervised learning, reinforcement learning, and self-supervised learning.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p01] Supervised learning pairs inputs and desired outputs.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p01] The learning task is to produce the desired output for each input.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p01] In this case, the cost is related to eliminating incorrect outputs.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p01] A commonly used cost is the mean-squared error, which tries to minimize the average squared error between the network's output and the desired output.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p01] Tasks suited for supervised learning include pattern recognition (classification) and regression (function approximation).
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p01] Supervised learning is applicable to sequential data (e.g., for handwriting, speech and gesture recognition).
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p01] This can be thought of as learning with a "teacher", in the form of a function that provides continuous feedback.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p01] In unsupervised learning, input data is given along with the cost function for the data $\textstyle x$ and the output, without an "answer sheet".
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p01] The cost function is dependent on the task (the model domain) and reflects *a priori* assumptions (implicit model properties, its parameters and the observed variables).
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p01] For example, the model $\textstyle f(x)=a$ treats $\textstyle a$ is a constant and the cost $\textstyle C=E[(x-f(x))^{2}]$ .
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p01] Minimizing this cost produces a value of $\textstyle a$ that is equal to the mean of the data.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p01] The cost function can be much more complicated.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p01] Its form depends on the application: for example, in compression it could be related to the mutual information between $\textstyle x$ and $\textstyle f(x)$ , whereas in statistical modeling, it could be related to the posterior probability (in both examples, those quantities are maximized).
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p01] Unsupervised learning is typically applied to estimation problems; applications include clustering, the estimation of statistical distributions, compression, and filtering.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p01] Self-supervised learning (SSL) is a paradigm in machine learning where a model is trained on a task using the data itself to generate supervisory signals, rather than relying on externally-provided labels.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p01] In the context of neural networks, self-supervised learning aims to leverage inherent structures or relationships within the input data to create meaningful training signals.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p01] SSL tasks are designed so that solving them requires capturing essential features or relationships in the data.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p01] The input data is typically augmented or transformed in a way that creates pairs of related samples, where one sample serves as the input, and the other is used to formulate the supervisory signal.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p01] This augmentation can involve introducing noise, cropping, rotation, or other transformations.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p01] Self-supervised learning more closely imitates the way humans learn to classify objects.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p01] During SSL, the model learns in two steps.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p01] First, the task is solved based on an auxiliary or pretext classification task using pseudo-labels, which help to initialize the model parameters.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p01] Next, the actual task is performed with supervised or unsupervised learning.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p01] Self-supervised learning has produced promising results in recent years, and has found practical application in fields such as audio processing, and is being used by Facebook and others for speech recognition.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p01] In applications such as playing video games, an actor takes a string of actions, receiving a generally unpredictable response from the environment (the game) after each one.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p01] The goal is to win the game (get the highest score).
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p01] In reinforcement learning, the aim is to weight the network to increase the score.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p01] After each action the game generates an observation and an instantaneous cost, according to its rules.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p01] The rules and the long-term cost can only be estimated.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p01] At any juncture, the agent decides whether to explore new actions to uncover their costs or to exploit prior learning to proceed more quickly.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p01] Formally, the environment is modeled as a Markov decision process (MDP) with states $\textstyle {s_{1},...,s_{n}}\in S$ and actions $\textstyle {a_{1},...,a_{m}}\in A$ .
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p01] Taken together, the two define a Markov chain (MC).
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p01] The aim is to discover the lowest-cost MC.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p01] Self-learning was introduced in 1982 along with a *crossbar adaptive array* (CAA) NN that could teach itself.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p01] It is a system with only one input, situation s, and only one output, action (or behavior) a.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p01] It has neither external advice input nor external reinforcement from the environment.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p01] The CAA computes, in a crossbar fashion, both decisions about actions and emotions (feelings) about encountered situations.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p01] The system is driven by the interaction between cognition and emotion.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p01] The backpropagated value (secondary reinforcement) is the emotion toward the consequence situation.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p01] The CAA exists in two environments, its behavioral environment, and its genetic environment, from which it receives initial emotions (only once) about to be encountered situations in the behavioral environment.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p01] Having received the genome vector (species vector) from the genetic environment, the CAA will learn a goal-seeking behavior, in the behavioral environment that contains both desirable and undesirable situations.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p01] Neuroevolution can create NN topologies and weights using evolutionary computation.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p01] It is competitive with gradient descent approaches.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p01] Neuroevolution may be less prone to get caught in "dead ends".
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p01] Topological deep learning, introduced in 2017, integrates topology with deep neural networks to address high-order data.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p01] Initially rooted in algebraic topology, TDL evolved into a versatile framework incorporating tools from mathematical disciplines such as differential topology and geometric topology.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p01] In a Bayesian framework, a distribution over the set of allowed models is chosen to minimize cost.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p01] Evolutionary methods, gene expression programming, simulated annealing, expectation–maximization, non-parametric methods and particle swarm optimization are other learning algorithms.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p01] Convergent recursion is a learning algorithm for cerebellar model articulation controller (CMAC) neural networks.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p01] Learning can be either stochastic or batch.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p01] Stochastic learning creates a weight adjustment for each sample.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p01] In batch learning, weights are adjusted based on a batch of inputs, accumulating errors over the batch.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p01] Stochastic learning introduces "noise" into the process, using the local gradient calculated from one data point; this reduces the chance of the network getting stuck in local minima.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p01] However, batch learning typically yields a faster, more stable descent to a local minimum, since each update is performed in the direction of the batch's average error.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p01] A common compromise is to use "mini-batches", small batches with samples in each batch selected stochastically from the entire data set.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p01] Types of neural networks (NN) include a family of techniques.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p01] The simplest types have static components, including number of units, number of layers, unit weights and topology.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p01] Some types allow/require learning to be "supervised" by the operator, while others operate independently.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p01] Some types operate purely in hardware, while others are purely software and run on general purpose computers.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p01] The choice of model depends on the data and the application.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p01] Models that work well with textual data are typically not the best choice for image data, etc.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p01] An important element is which training/learning the model uses.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p01] Neural architecture search (NAS) uses machine learning to automate NN design.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p01] NAS has yielded networks that compare well with hand-designed systems.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p01] The basic algorithm is to propose a candidate model, evaluate it against a dataset, and use the results as feedback to teach the NAS network.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p01] Efforts include AutoML and AutoKeras. scikit-learn library provides functions to help with building a deep network from scratch.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p01] Hyperparameters are design choices (they are not learned).
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p01] The multilayer perceptron is a universal function approximator, as proven by the universal approximation theorem.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p01] However, the proof does not specify the number of neurons required, the network topology, the weights or the learning parameters.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p01] A recurrent architecture with rational-valued weights (as opposed to full precision real number-valued weights) has the power of a universal Turing machine, using a finite number of neurons and linear connections.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p01] Further, the use of irrational values for weights results in a machine with super-Turing power.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p01] A model's "capacity" property is its ability to model any given function.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p01] It is related to the amount of information that can be stored in the network and to the notion of complexity.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p01] Information capacity and the VC dimension are two metrics.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p01] The capacity of a network of standard neurons (not convolutional) can be derived by four rules that derive from considering a neuron as an electrical element.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p01] The information capacity captures the functions that the network can model given any data as input.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p01] The VC dimension uses the principles of measure theory and finds the maximum capacity under optimal circumstances, given input data in a specific form.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p01] The VC Dimension for arbitrary inputs is half the information capacity of a perceptron.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p01] The VC Dimension for arbitrary points is sometimes referred to as Memory Capacity.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p01] Models may not consistently converge on a single solution, because the system may get stuck in a local minima.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p01] Alternatively, the optimization method used might not guarantee to converge should it begin far from any local minima.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p01] Thirdly, for sufficiently large data or parameters, some methods are impractically slow/expensive.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p01] Training may also cross some saddle point that may then prevent access to the solution.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p01] When the width of a network approaches infinity, it is well described by its first order Taylor expansion throughout training, and so inherits the convergence behavior of affine models.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p01] When parameter numbers are small, NNs often fit target functions from low to high frequencies.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p01] This behavior is referred to as spectral bias, or the frequency principle.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p01] This phenomenon is the opposite of the behavior of some well-studied iterative numerical schemes such as the Jacobi method.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p01] Deeper neural networks are more biased towards low frequency functions.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p01] Applications that must generalize well to unseen examples, must avoid over-training.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p01] This arises in convoluted or over-specified systems when the network capacity is much larger than needed.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p01] Cross-validation and similar techniques can check for over-training and select appropriate hyperparameters to minimize generalization error.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p01] Supervised neural networks that use a mean squared error (MSE) cost function can use formal statistical methods to determine the confidence of the trained model.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p01] The MSE on a validation set can be used as an estimate for variance.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p01] This value can then be used to calculate the confidence interval of network output, assuming a normal distribution.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p01] A confidence analysis made this way is statistically valid as long as the output probability distribution stays the same and the network is not modified.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p01] By adopting a softmax activation function, a generalization of the logistic function, on the output layer of the neural network (or a softmax component in a component-based network) for categorical target variables, the outputs can be interpreted as posterior probabilities.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p01] This is useful in classification as it gives a certainty measure.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p01] Neural networks support a broad range of applications in image processing, speech recognition, natural language processing, finance, and medicine.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p01] Because of their ability to model and reproduce nonlinear processes, neural networks have found applications in many disciplines.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p01] NNs have been used to diagnose cancers and to distinguish highly invasive cancer cell lines from less invasive lines using only cell shape data.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p01] NNs have been used to accelerate reliability analysis of infrastructures subject to natural disasters and to predict settling in building foundations.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p01] They are used to mitigate flooding by modelling rainfall-runoff.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p01] NNs have been used for building black-box models in geoscience: hydrology, ocean modelling and coastal engineering, and geomorphology.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p01] NNs have been employed in cybersecurity, with the objective to discriminate between legitimate and malicious activities.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p01] For example, machine learning has been used for classifying Android malware, for identifying domains belonging to threat actors and for detecting URLs posing a security risk.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p01] Research is underway on penetration testing, for detecting botnets, credit cards frauds, and network intrusions.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p01] NNs have been proposed as a tool to solve partial differential equations in physics and simulate the properties of many-body open quantum systems.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p01] In brain research NNs have studied short-term behavior of individual neurons, the dynamics of neural circuitry arise from interactions between individual neurons and how behavior can arise from abstract neural modules that represent complete subsystems.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p01] Studies considered long-and short-term plasticity of neural systems and their relation to learning and memory from the individual neuron to the system level.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p01] NNs show promise in profiling a user's interests from photos and discovering new stable materials by efficiently predicting the total energy of crystals.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p01] NNs are employed in computer vision tasks such as image classification, object and facial recognition, and image segmentation.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p01] They have been applied to automated surveillance medical imaging for diagnosis.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p01] NNs are used for speaker identification, speech-to-text, and text-to-speech conversion.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p01] NNs have conquered large vocabulary continuous speech recognition, outperforming traditional techniques.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p01] These advancements have enabled the development of more accurate and efficient voice-activated systems, enhancing user interfaces in technology products.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p01] In natural language processing, NNs are used for tasks such as text classification, sentiment analysis, machine translation, to answer free-form questions, act as chatbots, and to summarize and analyze texts.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p01] This has implications for automated customer service, content moderation, and language understanding technologies.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p01] NNs are used to model dynamic systems for tasks such as system identification, control design, autonomous vehicles, and optimization.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p01] Large financial institutions use AI to assist with their investment practices.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p01] BlackRock's AI engine, Aladdin, is used both within the company and by clients to help with investment decisions.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p01] Its functions include the use of natural language processing to analyze text such as news, broker reports, and social media feeds.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p01] It then gauges the sentiment on the companies mentioned and assigns a score.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p01] Banks such as UBS and Deutsche Bank use SQREEM (Sequential Quantum Reduction and Extraction Model) to mine data to develop consumer profiles and match them with wealth management products.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p01] They enhance diagnostic accuracy, especially by interpreting complex medical imaging for early disease detection, and by predicting patient outcomes for personalized treatment planning.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p01] In drug discovery, NNs speed up the identification of potential drug candidates and predict their efficacy and safety, significantly reducing development time and costs.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p01] Additionally, their application in personalized medicine and healthcare data analysis allows tailored therapies and efficient patient care management.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p01] Neural networks are widely applied in cybersecurity for anomaly detection, malware classification, and intrusion detection.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p01] By learning patterns of normal system or network behavior, NNs can identify deviations that indicate malicious activity.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p01] Transformers are used for content creation across numerous industries.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p01] They can analyze samples and produce outputs that match the style of an artist or musician.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p01] For instance, DALL-E trained on 650 million pairs of images and texts and can create artworks based on user text.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p01] Companies such as AIVA and Jukedeck have used transformers to create original music.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p01] NNs have been used to create personalized advertisements.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p01] Film production companies have used NNs to analyze the financial success of a film.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p01] NNs have found uses in video game creation.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p02] NNs require millions of training samples to become functional.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p02] As of 2026, training a commercial LLM (GPT, Grok, Gemini) typically required hundreds of thousands of computers, and cost 10s of millions of dollars.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p02] A central claim of NNs is that they embody new and powerful general principles for processing information.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p02] However, at root they use statistical long-developed methods.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p02] Neural networks require enormous computing resources for training.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p02] While the brain requires only 20 watts of power, training commercial transformers requires (2026) data centers with hundreds of megawatts.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p02] From 1991 to 2015, computing power, especially as delivered by GPGPUs (on GPUs), increased around a million-fold, enabling the use of the backpropagation algorithm.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p02] Neuromorphic engineering or a physical neural network constructed non-von-Neumann chips to directly implement neural networks in circuitry.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p02] For example, Alphabet introduced custom chips (Tensor Processing Unit).
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p02] The statistical properties of input data may change over time, a phenomenon known as concept drift or non-stationarity.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p02] Drift can reduce predictive accuracy and lead to unreliable or biased decisions if it is not detected and corrected.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p02] In practice, this means that the model's accuracy in deployment may differ substantially from levels observed during training.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p02] Neural networks are dependent on the quality of their training data; low quality data can lead the model to product poor results.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p02] Biased data produces biased results, requiring trainers to detect and correct them.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p02] For example, data that underrepresents some demographic groups may prevent cause errors, e.g., in facial recognition and law enforcement.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p02] In 2018, Amazon scrapped a recruiting tool because the model favored men over women for jobs in software engineering due to the larger number of male workers in the field.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p02] The system penalized resumes with the word "woman" or the name of a women's college.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p02] One corrective is to add synthetic data to offset the bias.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p02] NNs are "black box" systems that have complicated understanding of their decision-making processes.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p02] NNs are further vulnerable to adversarial examples ("poison"), that can cause incorrect predictions.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p02] These concerns have led to increased research in explainable artificial intelligence (XAI), robust machine learning, and hybrid AI approaches that combine neural learning with symbolic reasoning.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p02] Advocates of hybrid models also say that such a mixture can better capture the mechanisms of the human mind.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p02] Progress has included local vs. non-local learning and shallow vs. deep architectures.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/artificial-neural-network-p02] Analyzing human thought (a biological neural network) has also proven difficult.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/data-labeling] Labels can be obtained by having humans make judgments about a given piece of unlabeled data.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/data-labeling] Labeled data is significantly more expensive to obtain than the raw unlabeled data.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/data-labeling] The quality of labeled data directly influences the performance of supervised machine learning models in operation, as these models learn from the provided labels.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/data-labeling] In 2006, Fei-Fei Li, the co-director of the Stanford Human-Centered AI Institute, initiated research to improve the artificial intelligence models and algorithms for image recognition by significantly enlarging the training data.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/data-labeling] The researchers downloaded millions of images from the World Wide Web and a team of undergraduates started to apply labels for objects to each image.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/data-labeling] In 2007, Li outsourced the data labeling work on Amazon Mechanical Turk, an online marketplace for digital piece work.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/data-labeling] The 3.2 million images that were labeled by more than 49,000 workers formed the basis for ImageNet, one of the largest hand-labeled database for outline of object recognition.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/data-labeling] After obtaining a labeled dataset, machine learning models can be applied to the data so that new unlabeled data can be presented to the model and a likely label can be guessed or predicted for that piece of unlabeled data.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/data-labeling] Algorithmic decision-making is subject to programmer-driven bias as well as data-driven bias.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/data-labeling] Training data that relies on bias labeled data will result in prejudices and omissions in a predictive model, despite the machine learning algorithm being legitimate.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/data-labeling] The labeled data used to train a specific machine learning algorithm needs to be a statistically representative sample to not bias the results.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/data-labeling] For example, in facial recognition systems underrepresented groups are subsequently often misclassified if the labeled data available to train has not been representative of the population,.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/data-labeling] In 2018, a study by Joy Buolamwini and Timnit Gebru demonstrated that two facial analysis datasets that have been used to train facial recognition algorithms, IJB-A and Adience, are composed of 79.6% and 86.2% lighter skinned humans respectively.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/data-labeling] Human annotators are prone to errors and biases when labeling data.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/data-labeling] This can lead to inconsistent labels and affect the quality of the data set.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/data-labeling] The inconsistency can affect the machine learning model's ability to generalize well.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/data-labeling] Certain fields, such as legal document analysis or medical imaging, require annotators with specialized domain knowledge.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/data-labeling] Without the expertise, the annotations or labeled data may be inaccurate, negatively impacting the machine learning model's performance in a real-world scenario.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p01] In machine learning, **deep learning** (**DL**) focuses on utilizing multilayered neural networks to perform tasks such as classification, regression, and representation learning.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p01] The field takes inspiration from biological neuroscience and revolves around stacking artificial neurons into layers and "training" them to process data.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p01] The adjective "deep" refers to the use of multiple layers (ranging from three to several hundred or thousands) in the network.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p01] Methods used can be supervised, semi-supervised or unsupervised.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p01] Some common deep learning network architectures include fully connected networks, deep belief networks, recurrent neural networks, convolutional neural networks, generative adversarial networks, transformers, and neural radiance fields.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p01] Early forms of neural networks were inspired by information processing and distributed communication nodes in biological systems, particularly the human brain.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p01] However, current neural networks do not intend to model the brain function of organisms, and are generally seen as low-quality models for that purpose.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p01] Fundamentally, deep learning refers to a class of machine learning algorithms in which a hierarchy of layers is used to transform input data into a progressively more abstract and composite representation.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p01] For example, in an image recognition model, the raw input may be an image (represented as a tensor of pixels).
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p01] The first representational layer may attempt to identify basic shapes such as lines and circles, the second layer may compose and encode arrangements of edges, the third layer may encode a nose and eyes, and the fourth layer may recognize that the image contains a face.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p01] Importantly, a deep learning process can learn which features to optimally place at which level *on its own*.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p01] Prior to deep learning, machine learning techniques often involved hand-crafted feature engineering to transform the data into a more suitable representation for a classification algorithm to operate on.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p01] In the deep learning approach, features are not hand-crafted and the model discovers useful feature representations from the data automatically.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p01] This does not eliminate the need for hand-tuning; for example, varying numbers of layers and layer sizes can provide different degrees of abstraction.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p01] The word "deep" in "deep learning" refers to the number of layers through which the data is transformed.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p01] More precisely, deep learning systems have a substantial *credit assignment path* (CAP) depth.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p01] The CAP is the chain of transformations from input to output.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p01] CAPs describe potentially causal connections between input and output.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p01] For a feedforward neural network, the depth of the CAPs is that of the network and is the number of hidden layers plus one (as the output layer is also parameterized).
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p01] For recurrent neural networks, in which a signal may propagate through a layer more than once, the CAP depth is potentially unlimited.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p01] No universally agreed-upon threshold of depth divides shallow learning from deep learning, but most researchers agree that deep learning involves CAP depth higher than two.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p01] CAP of depth two has been shown to be a universal approximator in the sense that it can emulate any function.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p01] Beyond that, more layers do not add to the function approximator ability of the network.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p01] Deep models (CAP > two) are able to extract better features than shallow models and hence, extra layers help in learning the features effectively.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p01] Deep learning architectures can be constructed with a greedy layer-by-layer method.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p01] Deep learning helps to disentangle these abstractions and pick out which features improve performance.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p01] Deep learning algorithms can be applied to unsupervised learning tasks.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p01] This is an important benefit because unlabeled data is more abundant than labeled data.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p01] Examples of deep structures that can be trained in an unsupervised manner are deep belief networks.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p01] The term *deep learning* was introduced to the machine learning community by Rina Dechter in 1986, and to artificial neural networks by Igor Aizenberg and colleagues in 2000, in the context of Boolean threshold neurons.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p01] The etymology of the term is more complicated.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p01] Deep neural networks are generally interpreted in terms of the universal approximation theorem or probabilistic inference.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p01] The classic universal approximation theorem concerns the capacity of feedforward neural networks with a single hidden layer of finite size to approximate continuous functions.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p01] In 1989, the first proof was published by George Cybenko for sigmoid activation functions and was generalised to feed-forward multi-layer architectures in 1991 by Kurt Hornik.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p01] Recent work also showed that universal approximation also holds for non-bounded activation functions such as Kunihiko Fukushima's rectified linear unit.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p01] The universal approximation theorem for deep neural networks concerns the capacity of networks with bounded width but the depth is allowed to grow.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p01] The probabilistic interpretation derives from the field of machine learning.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p01] It features inference, as well as the optimization concepts of training and testing, related to fitting and generalization, respectively.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p01] More specifically, the probabilistic interpretation considers the activation nonlinearity as a cumulative distribution function.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p01] The probabilistic interpretation led to the introduction of dropout as regularizer in neural networks.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p01] The probabilistic interpretation was introduced by researchers including Hopfield, Widrow and Narendra and popularized in surveys such as the one by Bishop.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p01] There are two types of artificial neural network (ANN): feedforward neural network (FNN) or multilayer perceptron (MLP) and recurrent neural networks (RNN).
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p01] RNNs have cycles in their connectivity structure, whereas FNNs do not.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p01] In the 1920s, Wilhelm Lenz and Ernst Ising created the Ising model which is essentially a non-learning RNN architecture consisting of neuron-like threshold elements.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p01] In 1972, Shun'ichi Amari made this architecture adaptive.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p01] His learning RNN was republished by John Hopfield in 1982.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p01] Other early recurrent neural networks were published by Kaoru Nakano in 1971.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p01] Already in 1948, Alan Turing produced work on "Intelligent Machinery" that was not published in his lifetime, containing "ideas related to artificial evolution and learning RNNs".
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p01] Frank Rosenblatt (1958) proposed the perceptron, an MLP with 3 layers: an input layer, a hidden layer with randomized weights that did not learn, and an output layer.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p01] He later published a 1962 book that also introduced variants and computer experiments, including a version with four-layer perceptrons "with adaptive preterminal networks" where the last two layers have learned weights (here he credits H.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p01] Joseph (1960) "functionally equivalent to a variation of" this four-layer system (the book mentions Joseph over 30 times).
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p01] Should Joseph therefore be considered the originator of proper adaptive multilayer perceptrons with learning hidden units?
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p01] Unfortunately, the learning algorithm was not a functional one, and fell into oblivion.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p01] The first working deep learning algorithm was the Group method of data handling, a method to train arbitrarily deep neural networks, published by Alexey Ivakhnenko and Lapa in 1965.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p01] They regarded it as a form of polynomial regression, or a generalization of Rosenblatt's perceptron to handle more complex, nonlinear, and hierarchical relationships.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p01] A 1971 paper described a deep network with eight layers trained by this method, which is based on layer by layer training through regression analysis.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p01] Superfluous hidden units are pruned using a separate validation set.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p01] Since the activation functions of the nodes are Kolmogorov-Gabor polynomials, these were also the first deep networks with multiplicative units or "gates".
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p01] The first deep learning multilayer perceptron trained by stochastic gradient descent was published in 1967 by Shun'ichi Amari.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p01] In computer experiments conducted by Amari's student Saito, a five layer MLP with two modifiable layers learned internal representations to classify non-linearily separable pattern classes.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p01] Subsequent developments in hardware and hyperparameter tunings have made end-to-end stochastic gradient descent the currently dominant training technique.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p01] The rectifier has become the most popular activation function for deep learning.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p01] Deep learning architectures for convolutional neural networks (CNNs) with convolutional layers and downsampling layers began with the Neocognitron introduced by Kunihiko Fukushima in 1979, though not trained by backpropagation.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p01] The terminology "back-propagating errors" was actually introduced in 1962 by Rosenblatt, but he did not know how to implement this, although Henry J.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p01] Kelley had a continuous precursor of backpropagation in 1960 in the context of control theory.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p01] The modern form of backpropagation was first published in Seppo Linnainmaa's master thesis (1970).
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p01] Paul Werbos applied backpropagation to neural networks in 1982 (his 1974 PhD thesis, reprinted in a 1994 book, did not yet describe the algorithm).
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p01] Rumelhart et al. popularised backpropagation but did not cite the original work.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p01] The time delay neural network (TDNN) was introduced in 1987 by Alex Waibel to apply CNN to phoneme recognition.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p01] In 1988, Wei Zhang applied a backpropagation-trained CNN to alphabet recognition.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p01] LeNet-5 (1998), a 7-level CNN by Yann LeCun et al., that classifies digits, was applied by several banks to recognize hand-written numbers on checks digitized in 32x32 pixel images.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p01] Recurrent neural networks (RNN) were further developed in the 1980s.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p01] Recurrence is used for sequence processing, and when a recurrent network is unrolled, it mathematically resembles a deep feedforward layer.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p01] Consequently, they have similar properties and issues, and their developments had mutual influences.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p01] In RNN, two early influential works were the Jordan network (1986) and the Elman network (1990), which applied RNN to study problems in cognitive psychology.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p01] In the 1980s, backpropagation did not work well for deep learning with long credit assignment paths.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p01] To overcome this problem, in 1991, Jürgen Schmidhuber proposed a hierarchy of RNNs pre-trained one level at a time by self-supervised learning where each RNN tries to predict its own next input, which is the next unexpected input of the RNN below.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p01] This "neural history compressor" uses predictive coding to learn internal representations at multiple self-organizing time scales.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p01] This can substantially facilitate downstream deep learning.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p01] The RNN hierarchy can be *collapsed* into a single RNN, by distilling a higher level *chunker* network into a lower level *automatizer* network.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p01] In 1993, a neural history compressor solved a "Very Deep Learning" task that required more than 1000 subsequent layers in an RNN unfolded in time.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p01] The "P" in ChatGPT refers to such pre-training.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p01] Sepp Hochreiter's diploma thesis (1991) implemented the neural history compressor, and identified and analyzed the vanishing gradient problem.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p01] Hochreiter proposed recurrent residual connections to solve the vanishing gradient problem.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p01] This led to the long short-term memory (LSTM), published in 1995.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p01] LSTM can learn "very deep learning" tasks with long credit assignment paths that require memories of events that happened thousands of discrete time steps before.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p01] That LSTM was not yet the modern architecture, which required a "forget gate", introduced in 1999, which became the standard RNN architecture.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p01] In 1991, Jürgen Schmidhuber also published adversarial neural networks that contest with each other in the form of a zero-sum game, where one network's gain is the other network's loss.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p01] In 2014, this principle was used in generative adversarial networks (GANs).
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p01] During 1985–1995, inspired by statistical mechanics, several architectures and methods were developed by Terry Sejnowski, Peter Dayan, Geoffrey Hinton, etc., including the Boltzmann machine, restricted Boltzmann machine, Helmholtz machine, and the wake-sleep algorithm.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p01] However, those were more computationally expensive compared to backpropagation.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p01] Boltzmann machine learning algorithm, published in 1985, was briefly popular before being eclipsed by the backpropagation algorithm in 1986.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p01] A 1988 network became state of the art in protein structure prediction, an early application of deep learning to bioinformatics.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p01] Both shallow and deep learning (e.g., recurrent nets) of ANNs for speech recognition have been explored for many years.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p01] These methods never outperformed non-uniform internal-handcrafting Gaussian mixture model/Hidden Markov model (GMM-HMM) technology based on generative models of speech trained discriminatively.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p01] Key difficulties have been analyzed, including gradient diminishing and weak temporal correlation structure in neural predictive models.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p01] Additional difficulties were the lack of training data and limited computing power.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p01] Most speech recognition researchers moved away from neural nets to pursue generative modeling.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p01] An exception was at SRI International in the late 1990s.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p01] Funded by the US government's NSA and DARPA, SRI researched in speech and speaker recognition.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p01] The speaker recognition team led by Larry Heck reported significant success with deep neural networks in speech processing in the 1998 NIST Speaker Recognition benchmark.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p01] It was deployed in the Nuance Verifier, representing the first major industrial application of deep learning.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p01] The raw features of speech, waveforms, later produced excellent larger-scale results.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p01] In 2003, LSTM became competitive with traditional speech recognizers on certain tasks.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p01] In 2006, Alex Graves, Santiago Fernández, Faustino Gomez, and Schmidhuber combined it with connectionist temporal classification (CTC) in stacks of LSTMs.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p01] In 2009, it became the first RNN to win a pattern recognition contest, in connected handwriting recognition.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p01] In 2006, publications by Geoff Hinton, Ruslan Salakhutdinov, Osindero and Teh deep belief networks were developed for generative modeling.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p01] They are trained by training one restricted Boltzmann machine, then freezing it and training another one on top of the first one, and so on, then optionally fine-tuned using supervised backpropagation.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p01] They could model high-dimensional probability distributions, such as the distribution of MNIST images, but convergence was slow.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p01] The impact of deep learning in industry began in the early 2000s, when CNNs already processed an estimated 10% to 20% of all the checks written in the US, according to Yann LeCun.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p01] Industrial applications of deep learning to large-scale speech recognition started around 2010.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p01] The 2009 NIPS Workshop on Deep Learning for Speech Recognition was motivated by the limitations of deep generative models of speech, and the possibility that given more capable hardware and large-scale data sets that deep neural nets might become practical.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p01] It was believed that pre-training DNNs using generative models of deep belief nets (DBN) would overcome the main difficulties of neural nets.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p01] The nature of the recognition errors produced by the two types of systems was characteristically different, offering technical insights into how to integrate deep learning into the existing highly efficient, run-time speech decoding system deployed by all major speech recognition systems.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p01] Analysis around 2009–2010, contrasting the GMM (and other generative speech models) vs.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p01] DNN models, stimulated early industrial investment in deep learning for speech recognition.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p01] That analysis was done with comparable performance (less than 1.5% in error rate) between discriminative DNNs and generative models.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p01] In 2010, researchers extended deep learning from TIMIT to large vocabulary speech recognition, by adopting large output layers of the DNN based on context-dependent HMM states constructed by decision trees.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p01] The deep learning revolution started around CNN- and GPU-based computer vision.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p01] Although CNNs trained by backpropagation had been around for decades and GPU implementations of NNs for years, including CNNs, faster implementations of CNNs on GPUs were needed to progress on computer vision.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p01] Later, as deep learning becomes widespread, specialized hardware and algorithm optimizations were developed specifically for deep learning.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p01] A key advance for the deep learning revolution was hardware advances, especially GPU.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p01] In 2009, Raina, Madhavan, and Andrew Ng reported a 100M deep belief network trained on 30 Nvidia GeForce GTX 280 GPUs, an early demonstration of GPU-based deep learning.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p01] They reported up to 70 times faster training.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p01] In 2011, a CNN named *DanNet* by Dan Ciresan, Ueli Meier, Jonathan Masci, Luca Maria Gambardella, and Jürgen Schmidhuber achieved for the first time superhuman performance in a visual pattern recognition contest, outperforming traditional methods by a factor of 3.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p01] They also showed how max-pooling CNNs on GPU improved performance significantly.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p01] In 2012, Andrew Ng and Jeff Dean created an FNN that learned to recognize higher-level concepts, such as cats, only from watching unlabeled images taken from YouTube videos.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p01] In October 2012, AlexNet by Alex Krizhevsky, Ilya Sutskever, and Geoffrey Hinton won the large-scale ImageNet competition by a significant margin over shallow machine learning methods.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p01] The success in image classification was then extended to the more challenging task of generating descriptions (captions) for images, often as a combination of CNNs and LSTMs.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p01] In 2014, the state of the art was training "very deep neural network" with 20 to 30 layers.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p01] In 2015, two techniques were developed to train very deep networks: the highway network was published in May 2015, and the residual neural network (ResNet) in Dec 2015.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p01] Around the same time, deep learning started impacting the field of art.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p01] Early examples included Google DeepDream (2015), and neural style transfer (2015), both of which were based on pretrained image classification neural networks, such as VGG-19.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p01] Generative adversarial network (GAN) by (Ian Goodfellow et al., 2014) (based on Jürgen Schmidhuber's principle of artificial curiosity) became state of the art in generative modeling during 2014-2018 period.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p01] Excellent image quality is achieved by Nvidia's StyleGAN (2018) based on the Progressive GAN by Tero Karras et al.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p01] Here the GAN generator is grown from small to large scale in a pyramidal fashion.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p01] Diffusion models (2015) eclipsed GANs in generative modeling since then, with systems such as DALL·E 2 (2022) and Stable Diffusion (2022).
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p01] In 2015, Google's speech recognition improved by 49% by an LSTM-based model, which they made available through Google Voice Search on smartphone.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p01] Deep learning is part of state-of-the-art systems in various disciplines, particularly computer vision and automatic speech recognition (ASR).
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p01] Results on commonly used evaluation sets such as TIMIT (ASR) and MNIST (image classification), as well as a range of large-vocabulary speech recognition tasks have steadily improved.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p01] Convolutional neural networks were superseded for ASR by LSTM. but are more successful in computer vision.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p01] Yoshua Bengio, Geoffrey Hinton and Yann LeCun were awarded the 2018 Turing Award for "conceptual and engineering breakthroughs that have made deep neural networks a critical component of computing".
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p01] that was not included in the training gives a weak signal for the oval shape, also resulting in a weak signal for the sea urchin output.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p01] An ANN is based on a collection of connected units called artificial neurons, (analogous to biological neurons in a biological brain).
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p01] Each connection (synapse) between neurons can transmit a signal to another neuron.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p01] The receiving (postsynaptic) neuron can process the signal(s) and then signal downstream neurons connected to it.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p01] Neurons may have state, generally represented by real numbers, typically between 0 and 1.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p01] Neurons and synapses may also have a weight that varies as learning proceeds, which can increase or decrease the strength of the signal that it sends downstream.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p01] Typically, neurons are organized in layers.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p01] Different layers may perform different kinds of transformations on their inputs.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p01] Signals travel from the first (input), to the last (output) layer, possibly after traversing the layers multiple times.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p01] The original goal of the neural network approach was to solve problems in the same way that a human brain would.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p01] Over time, attention focused on matching specific mental abilities, leading to deviations from biology such as backpropagation, or passing information in the reverse direction and adjusting the network to reflect that information.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p01] Neural networks have been used on a variety of tasks, including computer vision, speech recognition, machine translation, social network filtering, playing board and video games and medical diagnosis.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p01] As of 2017, neural networks typically have a few thousand to a few million units and millions of connections.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p01] Despite this number being several order of magnitude less than the number of neurons on a human brain, these networks can perform many tasks at a level beyond that of humans (e.g., recognizing faces, or playing "Go").
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p01] A **deep neural network** (**DNN**) is an artificial neural network with multiple layers between the input and output layers.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p01] There are different types of neural networks but they always consist of the same components: neurons, synapses, weights, biases, and functions.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p01] These components as a whole function in a way that mimics functions of the human brain, and can be trained like any other ML algorithm.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p01] For example, a DNN that is trained to recognize dog breeds will go over the given image and calculate the probability that the dog in the image is a certain breed.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p01] The user can review the results and select which probabilities the network should display (above a certain threshold, etc.) and return the proposed label.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p01] Each mathematical manipulation as such is considered a layer, and complex DNN have many layers, hence the name "deep" networks.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p01] DNNs can model complex non-linear relationships.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p01] DNN architectures generate compositional models where the object is expressed as a layered composition of primitives.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p01] The extra layers enable composition of features from lower layers, potentially modeling complex data with fewer units than a similarly performing shallow network.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p01] For instance, it was proved that sparse multivariate polynomials are exponentially easier to approximate with DNNs than with shallow networks.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p01] Deep architectures include many variants of a few basic approaches.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p01] Each architecture has found success in specific domains.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p01] It is not always possible to compare the performance of multiple architectures, unless they have been evaluated on the same data sets.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p01] DNNs are typically feedforward networks in which data flows from the input layer to the output layer without looping back.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p01] At first, the DNN creates a map of virtual neurons and assigns random numerical values, or "weights", to connections between them.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p01] The weights and inputs are multiplied and return an output between 0 and 1.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p01] If the network did not accurately recognize a particular pattern, an algorithm would adjust the weights.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p01] That way the algorithm can make certain parameters more influential, until it determines the correct mathematical manipulation to fully process the data.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p01] Recurrent neural networks, in which data can flow in any direction, are used for applications such as language modeling.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p01] Long short-term memory is particularly effective for this use.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p01] Convolutional neural networks (CNNs) are used in computer vision.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p01] CNNs also have been applied to acoustic modeling for automatic speech recognition (ASR).
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p01] As with ANNs, many issues can arise with naively trained DNNs.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p01] Two common issues are overfitting and computation time.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p01] DNNs are prone to overfitting because of the added layers of abstraction, which allow them to model rare dependencies in the training data.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p01] Regularization methods such as Ivakhnenko's unit pruning or weight decay ( $\ell _{2}$ -regularization) or sparsity ( $\ell _{1}$ -regularization) can be applied during training to combat overfitting.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p01] Alternatively dropout regularization randomly omits units from the hidden layers during training.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p01] This helps to exclude rare dependencies.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p01] Another interesting recent development is research into models of just enough complexity through an estimation of the intrinsic complexity of the task being modelled.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p01] This approach has been successfully applied for multivariate time series prediction tasks such as traffic prediction.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p01] Finally, data can be augmented via methods such as cropping and rotating such that smaller training sets can be increased in size to reduce the chances of overfitting.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p01] DNNs must consider many training parameters, such as the size (number of layers and number of units per layer), the learning rate, and initial weights.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p01] Sweeping through the parameter space for optimal parameters may not be feasible due to the cost in time and computational resources.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p01] Various tricks, such as batching (computing the gradient on several training examples at once rather than individual examples) speed up computation.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p01] Large processing capabilities of many-core architectures (such as GPUs or the Intel Xeon Phi) have produced significant speedups in training, because of the suitability of such processing architectures for the matrix and vector computations.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p01] Alternatively, engineers may look for other types of neural networks with more straightforward and convergent training algorithms.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p01] CMAC (cerebellar model articulation controller) is one such kind of neural network.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p01] It doesn't require learning rates or randomized initial weights.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p01] The training process can be guaranteed to converge in one step with a new batch of data, and the computational complexity of the training algorithm is linear with respect to the number of neurons involved.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p01] Since the 2010s, advances in both machine learning algorithms and computer hardware have led to more efficient methods for training deep neural networks that contain many layers of non-linear hidden units and a very large output layer.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p01] By 2019, graphics processing units (GPUs), often with AI-specific enhancements, had displaced CPUs as the dominant method for training large-scale commercial cloud AI .
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p01] OpenAI estimated the hardware computation used in the largest deep learning projects from AlexNet (2012) to AlphaZero (2017) and found a 300,000-fold increase in the amount of computation required, with a doubling-time trendline of 3.4 months.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p01] Special electronic circuits called deep learning processors were designed to speed up deep learning algorithms.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p01] Deep learning processors include neural processing units (NPUs) in Huawei cellphones and cloud computing servers such as tensor processing units (TPU) in the Google Cloud Platform.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p01] Cerebras Systems has also built a dedicated system to handle large deep learning models, the CS-2, based on the largest processor in the industry, the second-generation Wafer Scale Engine (WSE-2).
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p01] Atomically thin semiconductors are considered promising for energy-efficient deep learning hardware where the same basic device structure is used for both logic operations and data storage.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p01] In 2020, Marega et al. published experiments with a large-area active channel material for developing logic-in-memory devices and circuits based on floating-gate field-effect transistors (FGFETs).
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p01] Feldmann et al. proposed an integrated photonic hardware accelerator for parallel convolutional processing.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p01] The authors identify two key advantages of integrated photonics over its electronic counterparts: (1) massively parallel data transfer through wavelength division multiplexing in conjunction with frequency combs, and (2) extremely high data modulation speeds.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p01] Their system can execute trillions of multiply-accumulate operations per second, indicating the potential of integrated photonics in data-heavy AI applications.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p02] Large-scale automatic speech recognition is the first and most convincing successful case of deep learning.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p02] LSTM RNNs can learn "Very Deep Learning" tasks that involve multi-second intervals containing speech events separated by thousands of discrete time steps, where one time step corresponds to about 10 ms.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p02] LSTM with forget gates is competitive with traditional speech recognizers on certain tasks.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p02] The initial success in speech recognition was based on small-scale recognition tasks based on TIMIT.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p02] The data set contains 630 speakers from eight major dialects of American English, where each speaker reads 10 sentences.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p02] Its small size lets many configurations be tried.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p02] More importantly, the TIMIT task concerns phone-sequence recognition, which, unlike word-sequence recognition, allows weak phone bigram language models.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p02] This lets the strength of the acoustic modeling aspects of speech recognition be more easily analyzed.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p02] The error rates listed below, including these early results and measured as percent phone error rates (PER), have been summarized since 1991.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p02] More recent speech recognition models use Transformers or Temporal Convolution Networks with significant success and widespread applications.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p02] All major commercial speech recognition systems (e.g., Microsoft Cortana, Xbox, Skype Translator, Amazon Alexa, Google Now, Apple Siri, Baidu and iFlyTek voice search, and a range of Nuance speech products, etc.) are based on deep learning.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p02] A common evaluation set for image classification is the MNIST database data set.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p02] MNIST is composed of handwritten digits and includes 60,000 training examples and 10,000 test examples.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p02] As with TIMIT, its small size lets users test multiple configurations.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p02] A comprehensive list of results on this set is available.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p02] Deep learning-based image recognition has become "superhuman", producing more accurate results than human contestants.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p02] This first occurred in 2011 in recognition of traffic signs, and in 2014, with recognition of human faces.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p02] Deep learning-trained vehicles now interpret 360° camera views.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p02] Another example is Facial Dysmorphology Novel Analysis (FDNA) used to analyze cases of human malformation connected to a large database of genetic syndromes.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p02] Closely related to the progress that has been made in image recognition is the increasing application of deep learning techniques to various visual art tasks.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p02] Neural networks have been used for implementing language models since the early 2000s.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p02] LSTM helped to improve machine translation and language modeling.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p02] Other key techniques in this field are negative sampling and word embedding.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p02] Word embedding, such as *word2vec*, can be thought of as a representational layer in a deep learning architecture that transforms an atomic word into a positional representation of the word relative to other words in the dataset; the position is represented as a point in a vector space.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p02] Using word embedding as an RNN input layer allows the network to parse sentences and phrases using an effective compositional vector grammar.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p02] A compositional vector grammar can be thought of as probabilistic context free grammar (PCFG) implemented by an RNN.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p02] Recursive auto-encoders built atop word embeddings can assess sentence similarity and detect paraphrasing.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p02] Recent developments generalize word embedding to sentence embedding.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p02] Google Translate (GT) uses a large end-to-end long short-term memory (LSTM) network.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p02] Google Neural Machine Translation (GNMT) uses an example-based machine translation method in which the system "learns from millions of examples".
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p02] It translates "whole sentences at a time, rather than pieces".
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p02] Google Translate supports over one hundred languages.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p02] The network encodes the "semantics of the sentence rather than simply memorizing phrase-to-phrase translations".
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p02] GT uses English as an intermediate between most language pairs.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p02] A large percentage of candidate drugs fail to win regulatory approval.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p02] These failures are caused by insufficient efficacy (on-target effect), undesired interactions (off-target effects), or unanticipated toxic effects.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p02] Research has explored use of deep learning to predict the biomolecular targets, off-targets, and toxic effects of environmental chemicals in nutrients, household products and drugs.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p02] AtomNet is a deep learning system for structure-based rational drug design.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p02] AtomNet was used to predict novel candidate biomolecules for disease targets such as the Ebola virus and multiple sclerosis.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p02] In 2017 graph neural networks were used for the first time to predict various properties of molecules in a large toxicology data set.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p02] In 2019, generative neural networks were used to produce molecules that were validated experimentally all the way into mice.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p02] Recommendation systems have used deep learning to extract meaningful features for a latent factor model for content-based music and journal recommendations.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p02] Multi-view deep learning has been applied for learning user preferences from multiple domains.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p02] The model uses a hybrid collaborative and content-based approach and enhances recommendations in multiple tasks.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p02] An autoencoder ANN was used in bioinformatics, to predict gene ontology annotations and gene-function relationships.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p02] In medical informatics, deep learning was used to predict sleep quality based on data from wearables and predictions of health complications from electronic health record data.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p02] Deep neural networks have shown unparalleled performance in predicting protein structure, according to the sequence of the amino acids that make it up.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p02] In 2020, AlphaFold, a deep-learning based system, achieved a level of accuracy significantly higher than all previous computational methods.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p02] Deep neural networks can be used to estimate the entropy of a stochastic process through an arrangement called a Neural Joint Entropy Estimator (NJEE).
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p02] Such an estimation provides insights on the effects of input random variables on an independent random variable.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p02] Practically, the DNN is trained as a classifier that maps an input vector or matrix X to an output probability distribution over the possible classes of random variable Y, given input X.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p02] For example, in image classification tasks, the NJEE maps a vector of pixels' color values to probabilities over possible image classes.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p02] In practice, the probability distribution of Y is obtained by a Softmax layer with number of nodes that is equal to the alphabet size of Y.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p02] NJEE uses continuously differentiable activation functions, such that the conditions for the universal approximation theorem holds.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p02] It is shown that this method provides a strongly consistent estimator and outperforms other methods in cases of large alphabet sizes.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p02] Deep learning has been shown to produce competitive results in medical applications such as cancer cell classification, lesion detection, organ segmentation and image enhancement.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p02] Modern deep learning tools demonstrate the high accuracy of detecting various diseases and the helpfulness of their use by specialists to improve the diagnosis efficiency.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p02] Finding the appropriate mobile audience for mobile advertising is always challenging, since many data points must be considered and analyzed before a target segment can be created and used in ad serving by any ad server.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p02] Deep learning has been used to interpret large, many-dimensioned advertising datasets.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p02] Many data points are collected during the request/serve/click internet advertising cycle.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p02] This information can form the basis of machine learning to improve ad selection.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p02] Deep learning has been successfully applied to inverse problems such as denoising, super-resolution, inpainting, and film colorization.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p02] These applications include learning methods such as "Shrinkage Fields for Effective Image Restoration" which trains on an image dataset, and Deep Image Prior, which trains on the image that needs restoration.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p02] Deep learning is being applied to financial fraud detection, tax evasion detection, and anti-money laundering.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p02] In November 2023, researchers at Google DeepMind and Lawrence Berkeley National Laboratory announced that they had developed an AI system known as GNoME.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p02] This system has contributed to materials science by discovering over 2 million new materials within a relatively short timeframe.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p02] GNoME employs deep learning techniques to efficiently explore potential material structures, achieving a significant increase in the identification of stable inorganic crystal structures.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p02] The system's predictions were validated through autonomous robotic experiments, demonstrating a noteworthy success rate of 71%.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p02] The data of newly discovered materials is publicly available through the Materials Project database, offering researchers the opportunity to identify materials with desired properties for various applications.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p02] This development has implications for the future of scientific discovery and the integration of AI in material science research, potentially expediting material innovation and reducing costs in product development.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p02] The use of AI and deep learning suggests the possibility of minimizing or eliminating manual lab experiments and allowing scientists to focus more on the design and analysis of unique compounds.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p02] The United States Department of Defense applied deep learning to train robots in new tasks through observation.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p02] Physics-informed neural networks have been used to solve partial differential equations in both forward and inverse problems in a data driven manner.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p02] One example is the reconstructing fluid flow governed by the Navier-Stokes equations.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p02] Using physics informed neural networks does not require the often expensive mesh generation that conventional CFD methods rely on.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p02] It is evident that geometric and physical constraints have a synergistic effect on neural PDE surrogates, thereby enhancing their efficacy in predicting stable and super long rollouts.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p02] Deep backward stochastic differential equation method is a numerical method that combines deep learning with Backward stochastic differential equation (BSDE).
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p02] This method is particularly useful for solving high-dimensional problems in financial mathematics.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p02] By leveraging the powerful function approximation capabilities of deep neural networks, deep BSDE addresses the computational challenges faced by traditional numerical methods in high-dimensional settings.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p02] Specifically, traditional methods like finite difference methods or Monte Carlo simulations often struggle with the curse of dimensionality, where computational cost increases exponentially with the number of dimensions.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p02] Deep BSDE methods, however, employ deep neural networks to approximate solutions of high-dimensional partial differential equations (PDEs), effectively reducing the computational burden.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p02] In addition, the integration of Physics-informed neural networks (PINNs) into the deep BSDE framework enhances its capability by embedding the underlying physical laws directly into the neural network architecture.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p02] This ensures that the solutions not only fit the data but also adhere to the governing stochastic differential equations.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p02] PINNs leverage the power of deep learning while respecting the constraints imposed by the physical models, resulting in more accurate and reliable solutions for financial mathematics problems.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p02] Image reconstruction is the reconstruction of the underlying images from the image-related measurements.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p02] Several works showed the better and superior performance of the deep learning methods compared to analytical methods for various applications, e.g., spectral imaging and ultrasound imaging.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p02] Traditional weather prediction systems solve a very complex system of partial differential equations.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p02] GraphCast is a deep learning based model, trained on a long history of weather data to predict how weather patterns change over time.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p02] It is able to predict weather conditions for up to 10 days globally, at a very detailed level, and in under a minute, with precision similar to state of the art systems.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p02] An epigenetic clock is a biochemical test that can be used to measure age.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p02] Galkin et al. used deep neural networks to train an epigenetic aging clock of unprecedented accuracy using >6,000 blood samples.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p02] The clock uses information from 1000 CpG sites and predicts people with certain conditions older than healthy controls: IBD, frontotemporal dementia, ovarian cancer, obesity.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p02] The aging clock was planned to be released for public use in 2021 by an Insilico Medicine spinoff company Deep Longevity.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p02] Deep learning is closely related to a class of theories of brain development (specifically, neocortical development) proposed by cognitive neuroscientists in the early 1990s.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p02] These developmental theories were instantiated in computational models, making them predecessors of deep learning systems.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p02] These developmental models share the property that various proposed learning dynamics in the brain (e.g., a wave of nerve growth factor) support the self-organization somewhat analogous to the neural networks utilized in deep learning models.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p02] Like the neocortex, neural networks employ a hierarchy of layered filters in which each layer considers information from a prior layer (or the operating environment), and then passes its output (and possibly the original input), to other layers.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p02] This process yields a self-organizing stack of transducers, well-tuned to their operating environment.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p02] A 1995 description stated, "...the infant's brain seems to organize itself under the influence of waves of so-called trophic-factors ... different regions of the brain become connected sequentially, with one layer of tissue maturing before another and so on until the whole brain is mature".
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p02] A variety of approaches have been used to investigate the plausibility of deep learning models from a neurobiological perspective.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p02] On the one hand, several variants of the backpropagation algorithm have been proposed in order to increase its processing realism.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p02] Other researchers have argued that unsupervised forms of deep learning, such as those based on hierarchical generative models and deep belief networks, may be closer to biological reality.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p02] In this respect, generative neural network models have been related to neurobiological evidence about sampling-based processing in the cerebral cortex.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p02] Although a systematic comparison between the human brain organization and the neuronal encoding in deep networks has not yet been established, several analogies have been reported.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p02] For example, the computations performed by deep learning units could be similar to those of actual neurons and neural populations.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p02] Similarly, the representations developed by deep learning models are similar to those measured in the primate visual system both at the single-unit and at the population levels.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p02] Facebook's AI lab performs tasks such as automatically tagging uploaded pictures with the names of the people in them.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p02] Google's DeepMind Technologies developed a system capable of learning how to play Atari video games using only pixels as data input.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p02] In 2015 they demonstrated their AlphaGo system, which learned the game of Go well enough to beat a professional Go player.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p02] Google Translate uses a neural network to translate between more than 100 languages.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p02] In 2017, Covariant.ai was launched, which focuses on integrating deep learning into factories.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p02] First developed as TAMER, a new algorithm called Deep TAMER was later introduced in 2018 during a collaboration between U.S.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p02] Army Research Laboratory (ARL) and UT researchers.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p02] Deep TAMER used deep learning to provide a robot with the ability to learn new tasks through observation.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p02] Using Deep TAMER, a robot learned a task with a human trainer, watching video streams or observing a human perform a task in-person.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p02] The robot later practiced the task with the help of some coaching from the trainer, who provided feedback such as "good job" and "bad job".
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p02] Deep learning has attracted both criticism and comment, in some cases from outside the field of computer science.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p02] A main criticism concerns the lack of theory surrounding some methods.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p02] Learning in the most common deep architectures is implemented using well-understood gradient descent.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p02] However, the theory surrounding other algorithms, such as contrastive divergence is less clear.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p02] What is it approximating?) Deep learning methods are often looked at as a black box, with most confirmations done empirically, rather than theoretically.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p02] With the support of Innovation Diffusion Theory (IDT), a study analyzed the diffusion of deep learning in BRICS and OECD countries using data from Google Trends.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p02] Some deep learning architectures display problematic behaviors, such as confidently classifying unrecognizable images as belonging to a familiar category of ordinary images (2014) and misclassifying minuscule perturbations of correctly classified images (2013).
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p02] Goertzel hypothesized that these behaviors are due to limitations in their internal representations and that these limitations would inhibit integration into heterogeneous multi-component artificial general intelligence (AGI) architectures.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p02] These issues may possibly be addressed by deep learning architectures that internally form states homologous to image-grammar decompositions of observed entities and events.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p02] Learning a grammar (visual or linguistic) from training data would be equivalent to restricting the system to commonsense reasoning that operates on concepts in terms of grammatical production rules and is a basic goal of both human language acquisition and artificial intelligence (AI).
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p02] As deep learning moves from the lab into the world, research and experience show that artificial neural networks are vulnerable to hacks and deception.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p02] By identifying patterns that these systems use to function, attackers can modify inputs to ANNs in such a way that the ANN finds a match that human observers would not recognize.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p02] For example, an attacker can make subtle changes to an image such that the ANN finds a match even though the image looks to a human nothing like the search target.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p02] Such manipulation is termed an "adversarial attack".
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p02] In 2016 researchers used one ANN to doctor images in trial and error fashion, identify another's focal points, and thereby generate images that deceived it.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p02] The modified images looked no different to human eyes.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p02] Another group showed that printouts of doctored images then photographed successfully tricked an image classification system.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p02] One defense is reverse image search, in which a possible fake image is submitted to a site such as TinEye that can then find other instances of it.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p02] Another group showed that certain psychedelic spectacles could fool a facial recognition system into thinking ordinary people were celebrities, potentially allowing one person to impersonate another.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p02] In 2017 researchers added stickers to stop signs and caused an ANN to misclassify them.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p02] ANNs can however be further trained to detect attempts at deception, potentially leading attackers and defenders into an arms race similar to the kind that already defines the malware defense industry.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p02] ANNs have been trained to defeat ANN-based anti-malware software by repeatedly attacking a defense with malware that was continually altered by a genetic algorithm until it tricked the anti-malware while retaining its ability to damage the target.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p02] In 2016, another group demonstrated that certain sounds could make the Google Now voice command system open a particular web address, and hypothesized that this could "serve as a stepping stone for further attacks (e.g., opening a web page hosting drive-by malware)".
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p02] In "data poisoning", false data is continually smuggled into a machine learning system's training set to prevent it from achieving mastery.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p02] The deep learning systems that are trained using supervised learning often rely on data that is created or annotated by humans, or both.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p02] It has been argued that not only low-paid clickwork (such as on Amazon Mechanical Turk) is regularly deployed for this purpose, but also implicit forms of human microwork that are often not recognized as such.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p02] The philosopher Rainer Mühlhoff distinguishes five types of "machinic capture" of human microwork to generate training data: (1) gamification (the embedding of annotation or computation tasks in the flow of a game), (2) "trapping and tracking" (e.g.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/deep-learning-p02] CAPTCHAs for image recognition or click-tracking on Google search results pages), (3) exploitation of social motivations (e.g. tagging faces on Facebook to obtain labeled facial images), (4) information mining (e.g. by leveraging quantified-self devices such as activity trackers) and (5) clickwork.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p01] Statistics and mathematical optimisation methods compose the foundations of machine learning.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p01] Data mining is a related field of study, focusing on exploratory data analysis (EDA) through unsupervised learning.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p01] From a theoretical viewpoint, probably approximately correct learning provides a mathematical and statistical framework for describing machine learning.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p01] Most traditional machine learning and deep learning algorithms can be described as empirical risk minimisation under this framework.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p01] The term *machine learning* was coined in 1959 by Arthur Samuel, an IBM employee and pioneer in the field of computer gaming and artificial intelligence.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p01] The synonym *self-teaching computers* was also used during this time period.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p01] The earliest machine learning program was introduced in the 1950s, when Samuel invented a computer program that calculated the chance of winning in checkers for each side, but the history of machine learning is rooted in decades of efforts to study human cognitive processes.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p01] In 1949, Canadian psychologist Donald Hebb published the book *The Organization of Behavior*, in which he introduced a theoretical neural structure formed by certain interactions among nerve cells.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p01] The Hebbian theory of neuron interaction set the groundwork for how many machine learning algorithms work, with connected artificial neurons changing the strength of their connections based on data.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p01] Other researchers who have studied human cognitive systems contributed to the modern machine learning technologies as well, including Walter Pitts and Warren McCulloch, who proposed the first mathematical model of neural networks including algorithms that mirror human thought processes.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p01] By the early 1960s, an experimental "learning machine" with punched tape memory, called Cybertron, had been developed by Raytheon Company to analyse sonar signals, electrocardiograms, and speech patterns using rudimentary reinforcement learning.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p01] It was repetitively "trained" by a human operator/teacher to recognise patterns and equipped with a "goof" button to cause it to reevaluate incorrect decisions.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p01] A representative book on research into machine learning during the 1960s was Nils Nilsson's book "Learning Machines", dealing mostly with machine learning for pattern classification.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p01] Interest related to pattern recognition continued into the 1970s, as described by Duda and Hart in 1973.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p01] In 1981, a report was given on using teaching strategies so that an artificial neural network learns to recognise 40 characters (26 letters, 10 digits, and 4 special symbols) from a computer terminal.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p01] This follows Alan Turing's proposal in his paper "Computing Machinery and Intelligence", in which the question, "Can machines think?", is replaced by asking whether machines can convincingly imitate a human in its responses to human-posed questions.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p01] In 2014 Ian Goodfellow and others introduced generative adversarial networks (GANs) which could produce realistic synthetic data.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p01] By 2016 AlphaGo had won against top human players in Go using reinforcement learning techniques.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p01] As a scientific endeavour, machine learning grew out of the quest for artificial intelligence (AI).
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p01] In the early days of AI as an academic discipline, some researchers were interested in having machines learn from data.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p01] They attempted to approach the problem with various symbolic methods, as well as what were then termed "neural networks"; these were mostly perceptrons and other models that were later found to be reinventions of the generalised linear models of statistics.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p01] Probabilistic reasoning was also employed, especially in automated medical diagnosis.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p01] However, an increasing emphasis on the logical, knowledge-based approach caused a rift between AI and machine learning.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p01] Probabilistic systems were plagued by theoretical and practical problems of data acquisition and representation.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p01] By 1980, expert systems had come to dominate AI, and statistics was out of favour.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p01] Work on symbolic/knowledge-based learning continued within AI, leading to inductive logic programming (ILP), but the more statistical line of research was now outside the field of AI proper, in pattern recognition and information retrieval.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p01] Neural network research was abandoned by AI and computer science around the same time.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p01] This subfield, termed "connectionism", was continued by researchers from other disciplines, including John Hopfield, David Rumelhart, and Geoffrey Hinton.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p01] Their main success came in the mid-1980s with the reinvention of backpropagation.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p01] Machine learning (ML), reorganised and recognised as its own field, started to flourish in the 1990s.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p01] The field changed its goal from achieving artificial intelligence to tackling solvable problems of a practical nature.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p01] It shifted focus away from the symbolic approaches it had inherited from AI, and toward methods and models borrowed from statistics, fuzzy logic, and probability theory.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p01] There is a close connection between machine learning and compression.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p01] A system that predicts the posterior probabilities of a sequence given its entire history can be used for optimal data compression (by using arithmetic coding on the output distribution).
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p01] Conversely, an optimal compressor can be used for prediction (by finding the symbol that compresses best, given the previous history).
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p01] This equivalence has been used as a justification for using data compression as a benchmark for "general intelligence".
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p01] An alternative view can show compression algorithms implicitly map strings into implicit feature space vectors, and compression-based similarity measures compute similarity within these feature spaces.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p01] For each compressor C(.) we define an associated vector space ℵ, such that C(.) maps an input string x, corresponding to the vector norm ||~x||.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p01] An exhaustive examination of the feature spaces underlying all compression algorithms is precluded by space; instead, feature vectors chooses to examine three representative lossless compression methods, LZW, LZ77, and PPM.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p01] According to AIXI theory, a connection more directly explained in Hutter Prize, the best possible compression of x is the smallest possible software that generates x.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p01] For example, in that model, a zip file's compressed size includes both the zip file and the unzipping software, since you can not unzip it without both, but there may be an even smaller combined form.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p01] Examples of AI-powered audio/video compression software include NVIDIA Maxine, AIVC.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p01] Examples of software that can perform AI-powered image compression include OpenCV, TensorFlow, MATLAB's Image Processing Toolbox (IPT) and High-Fidelity Generative Image Compression.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p01] In unsupervised machine learning, k-means clustering can be utilized to compress data by grouping similar data points into clusters.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p01] This technique simplifies handling extensive datasets that lack predefined labels and finds widespread use in fields such as image compression.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p01] Data compression aims to reduce the size of data files, enhancing storage efficiency and speeding up data transmission.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p01] K-means clustering, an unsupervised machine learning algorithm, is employed to partition a dataset into a specified number of clusters, k, each represented by the centroid of its points.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p01] This process condenses extensive datasets into a more compact set of representative points.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p01] Particularly beneficial in image and signal processing, k-means clustering aids in data reduction by replacing groups of data points with their centroids, thereby preserving the core information of the original data while significantly decreasing the required storage space.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p01] Large language models (LLMs) are also efficient lossless data compressors on some data sets, as demonstrated by DeepMind's research with the Chinchilla 70B model.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p01] Developed by DeepMind, Chinchilla 70B effectively compressed data, outperforming conventional methods such as Portable Network Graphics (PNG) for images and Free Lossless Audio Codec (FLAC) for audio.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p01] It achieved compression of image and audio data to 43.4% and 16.4% of their original sizes, respectively.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p01] There is, however, some reason to be concerned that the data set used for testing overlaps the LLM training data set, making it possible that the Chinchilla 70B model is only an efficient compression tool on data it has already been trained on.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p01] Data mining uses many machine learning methods, but with different goals; on the other hand, machine learning also employs data mining methods as "unsupervised learning" or as a preprocessing step to improve learner accuracy.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p01] Evaluated with respect to known knowledge, an uninformed (unsupervised) method will easily be outperformed by other supervised methods, while in a typical KDD task, supervised methods cannot be used due to the unavailability of training data.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p01] Machine learning also has intimate ties to optimization: Many learning problems are formulated as minimisation of some loss function on a training set of examples.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p01] Loss functions express the discrepancy between the predictions of the model being trained and the actual problem instances (for example, in classification, one wants to assign a label to instances, and models are trained to correctly predict the preassigned labels of a set of examples).
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p01] Characterizing the generalisation of various learning algorithms is an active topic of current research, especially for deep learning algorithms.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p01] Machine learning and statistics are closely related fields in terms of methods, but distinct in their principal goal: statistics draws population inferences from a sample, while machine learning finds generalisable predictive patterns.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p01] Conventional statistical analyses require the a priori selection of a model most suitable for the study data set.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p01] In addition, only significant or theoretically relevant variables based on previous experience are included for analysis.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p01] In contrast, machine learning is not built on a pre-structured model; rather, the data shape the model by detecting underlying patterns.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p01] The more variables (input) used to train the model, the more accurate the ultimate model will be.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p01] Leo Breiman distinguished two statistical modelling paradigms: the data model and the algorithmic model, wherein "algorithmic model" means more or less the machine learning algorithms like Random forest.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p01] Some statisticians have adopted methods from machine learning, producing the field of *statistical learning*.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p01] Analytical and computational techniques derived from deep-rooted physics of disordered systems can be extended to large-scale problems, including machine learning, e.g., to analyse the weight space of deep neural networks.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p01] Statistical physics is thus finding applications in the area of medical diagnostics.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p01] A core objective of a learner is to generalise from its experience.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p01] Generalisation in this context is the ability of a learning machine to perform accurately on new, unseen examples/tasks after having experienced a learning data set.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p01] The training examples come from some generally unknown probability distribution (considered representative of the space of occurrences) and the learner has to build a general model about this space that enables it to produce sufficiently accurate predictions in new cases.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p01] The computational analysis of machine learning algorithms and their performance is a branch of theoretical computer science known as computational learning theory.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p01] One major framework is the probably approximately correct learning model.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p01] Because training sets are finite and the future is uncertain, learning theory usually does not yield guarantees of the performance of algorithms.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p01] Instead, probabilistic bounds on the performance are quite common.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p01] The bias–variance decomposition is one way to quantify generalisation error.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p01] For the best performance in the context of generalisation, the complexity of the hypothesis should match the complexity of the function underlying the data.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p01] If the hypothesis is less complex than the function, then the model has underfitted the data.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p01] If the complexity of the model is increased in response, then the training error decreases.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p01] But if the hypothesis is too complex, then the model is subject to overfitting and generalisation will be poorer.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p01] In addition to performance bounds, learning theorists study the time complexity and feasibility of learning.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p01] In computational learning theory, a computation is considered feasible if it can be done in polynomial time.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p01] There are two kinds of time complexity results: Positive results show that a certain class of functions can be learned in polynomial time.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p01] Negative results show that certain classes cannot be learned in polynomial time.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p01] Although each algorithm has advantages and limitations, no single algorithm works for all problems.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p01] Supervised learning algorithms build a mathematical model of a set of data that contains both the inputs and the desired outputs.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p01] The data, known as training data, consists of a set of training examples.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p01] Each training example has one or more inputs and the desired output, also known as a supervisory signal.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p01] In the mathematical model, each training example is represented by an array or vector, sometimes called a feature vector, and the training data is represented by a matrix.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p01] Through iterative optimisation of an objective function, supervised learning algorithms learn a function that can be used to predict the output associated with new inputs.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p01] An optimal function allows the algorithm to correctly determine the output for inputs that were not a part of the training data.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p01] An algorithm that improves the accuracy of its outputs or predictions over time is said to have learned to perform that task.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p01] Types of supervised-learning algorithms include active learning, classification and regression.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p01] Classification algorithms are used when the outputs are restricted to a limited set of values, while regression algorithms are used when the outputs can take any numerical value within a range.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p01] For example, in a classification algorithm that filters emails, the input is an incoming email, and the output is the folder in which to file the email.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p01] In contrast, regression is used for tasks such as predicting a person's height based on factors like age and genetics or forecasting future temperatures based on historical data.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p01] Similarity learning is an area of supervised machine learning closely related to regression and classification, but the goal is to learn from examples using a similarity function that measures how similar or related two objects are.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p01] It has applications in ranking, recommendation systems, visual identity tracking, face verification, and speaker verification.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p01] Unsupervised learning algorithms find structures in data that has not been labelled, classified or categorised.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p01] Instead of responding to feedback, unsupervised learning algorithms identify commonalities in the data and react based on the presence or absence of such commonalities in each new piece of data.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p01] Central applications of unsupervised machine learning include clustering, dimensionality reduction, and density estimation.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p01] Cluster analysis is the assignment of a set of observations into subsets (called *clusters*) so that observations within the same cluster are similar according to one or more predesignated criteria, while observations drawn from different clusters are dissimilar.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p01] Different clustering techniques make different assumptions on the structure of the data, often defined by some *similarity metric* and evaluated, for example, by *internal compactness*, or the similarity between members of the same cluster, and *separation*, the difference between clusters.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p01] Other methods are based on *estimated density* and *graph connectivity*.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p01] A special type of unsupervised learning called self-supervised learning involves training a model by generating the supervisory signal from the data itself.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p01] Dimensionality reduction is a process of reducing the number of random variables under consideration by obtaining a set of principal variables.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p01] In other words, it is a process of reducing the dimension of the feature set, also called the "number of features".
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p01] Most of the dimensionality reduction techniques can be considered as either feature elimination or extraction.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p01] One of the popular methods of dimensionality reduction is principal component analysis (PCA).
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p01] PCA involves changing higher-dimensional data (e.g., 3D) to a smaller space (e.g., 2D).
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p01] The manifold hypothesis proposes that high-dimensional data sets lie along low-dimensional manifolds, and many dimensionality reduction techniques make this assumption, leading to the areas of manifold learning and manifold regularisation.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p01] Semi-supervised learning falls between unsupervised learning (without any labelled training data) and supervised learning (with completely labelled training data).
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p01] Some of the training examples are missing training labels, yet many machine-learning researchers have found that unlabelled data, when used in conjunction with a small amount of labelled data, can produce a considerable improvement in learning accuracy.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p01] In weakly supervised learning, the training labels are noisy, limited, or imprecise; however, these labels are often cheaper to obtain, resulting in larger effective training sets.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p01] Reinforcement learning is an area of machine learning concerned with how software agents ought to take actions in an environment to maximise some notion of cumulative reward.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p01] Due to its generality, the field is studied in many other disciplines, such as game theory, control theory, operations research, information theory, simulation-based optimisation, multi-agent systems, swarm intelligence, statistics and genetic algorithms.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p01] In reinforcement learning, the environment is typically represented as a Markov decision process (MDP).
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p01] Many reinforcement learning algorithms use dynamic programming techniques.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p01] Reinforcement learning algorithms do not assume knowledge of an exact mathematical model of the MDP and are used when exact models are infeasible.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p01] Reinforcement learning algorithms are used in autonomous vehicles or in learning to play a game against a human opponent.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p01] Other approaches have been developed which do not fit neatly into this three-fold categorisation, and sometimes more than one is used by the same machine learning system.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p01] For example, topic modelling, meta-learning.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p01] Self-learning, as a machine learning paradigm, was introduced in 1982 along with a neural network capable of self-learning, named *crossbar adaptive array* (CAA).
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p01] It gives a solution to the problem learning without any external reward, by introducing emotion as an internal reward.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p01] Emotion is used as a state evaluation of a self-learning agent.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p01] The CAA self-learning algorithm computes, in a crossbar fashion, both decisions about actions and emotions (feelings) about consequence situations.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p01] It is a system with only one input, situation, and only one output, action (or behaviour) a.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p01] There is neither a separate reinforcement input nor an advice input from the environment.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p01] The CAA exists in two environments, one is the behavioural environment where it behaves, and the other is the genetic environment, wherefrom it initially and only once receives initial emotions about situations to be encountered in the behavioural environment.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p01] After receiving the genome (species) vector from the genetic environment, the CAA learns a goal-seeking behaviour in an environment that contains both desirable and undesirable situations.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p01] Several learning algorithms aim at discovering better representations of the inputs provided during training.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p01] Classic examples include principal component analysis and cluster analysis.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p01] Feature learning algorithms, also called representation learning algorithms, often attempt to preserve the information in their input but also transform it in a way that makes it useful, often as a pre-processing step before performing classification or predictions.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p01] This technique allows reconstruction of the inputs coming from the unknown data-generating distribution, while not being necessarily faithful to configurations that are implausible under that distribution.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p01] This replaces manual feature engineering, and allows a machine to both learn the features and use them to perform a specific task.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p01] Feature learning can be either supervised or unsupervised.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p01] In supervised feature learning, features are learned using labelled input data.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p01] Examples include artificial neural networks, multilayer perceptrons, and supervised dictionary learning.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p01] In unsupervised feature learning, features are learned with unlabelled input data.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p01] Examples include dictionary learning, independent component analysis, autoencoders, matrix factorisation and various forms of clustering.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p01] Manifold learning algorithms attempt to do so under the constraint that the learned representation is low-dimensional.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p01] Sparse coding algorithms attempt to do so under the constraint that the learned representation is sparse, meaning that the mathematical model has many zeros.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p01] Multilinear subspace learning algorithms aim to learn low-dimensional representations directly from tensor representations for multidimensional data, without reshaping them into higher-dimensional vectors.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p01] Deep learning algorithms discover multiple levels of representation, or a hierarchy of features, with higher-level, more abstract features defined in terms of (or generating) lower-level features.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p01] It has been argued that an intelligent machine learns a representation that disentangles the underlying factors of variation that explain the observed data.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p01] Feature learning is motivated by the fact that machine learning tasks such as classification often require input that is mathematically and computationally convenient to process.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p01] However, real-world data such as images, video, and sensory data have not yielded attempts to algorithmically define specific features.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p01] An alternative is to discover such features or representations through examination, without relying on explicit algorithms.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p01] Sparse dictionary learning is a feature learning method where a training example is represented as a linear combination of basis functions and assumed to be a sparse matrix.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p01] The method is strongly NP-hard and difficult to solve approximately.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p01] A popular heuristic method for sparse dictionary learning is the *k*-SVD algorithm.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p01] Sparse dictionary learning has been applied in several contexts.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p01] In classification, the problem is to determine the class to which a previously unseen training example belongs.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p01] For a dictionary where each class has already been built, a new training example is associated with the class that is best sparsely represented by the corresponding dictionary.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p01] Sparse dictionary learning has also been applied in image denoising.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p01] The key idea is that a clean image patch can be sparsely represented by an image dictionary, but the noise cannot.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p01] In data mining, anomaly detection, also known as outlier detection, is the identification of rare items, events or observations that raise suspicions by differing significantly from the majority of the data.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p01] Typically, the anomalous items represent an issue such as bank fraud, a structural defect, medical problems or errors in a text.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p01] Anomalies are referred to as outliers, novelties, noise, deviations and exceptions.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p01] In particular, in the context of abuse and network intrusion detection, the interesting objects are often not rare, but unexpected bursts of inactivity.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p01] This pattern does not adhere to the common statistical definition of an outlier as a rare object.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p01] Many outlier detection methods (in particular, unsupervised algorithms) will fail on such data unless aggregated appropriately.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p01] Instead, a cluster analysis algorithm may be able to detect the micro-clusters formed by these patterns.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p01] Three broad categories of anomaly detection techniques exist.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p01] Unsupervised anomaly detection techniques detect anomalies in an unlabelled test data set under the assumption that the majority of the instances in the data set are normal, by looking for instances that seem to fit the least to the remainder of the data set.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p01] Supervised anomaly detection techniques require a data set that has been labelled as "normal" and "abnormal" and involves training a classifier (the key difference from many other statistical classification problems is the inherently unbalanced nature of outlier detection).
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p01] Semi-supervised anomaly detection techniques construct a model representing normal behaviour from a given normal training data set and then test the likelihood of a test instance being generated by the model.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p01] Robot learning is inspired by a multitude of machine learning methods, starting from supervised learning, reinforcement learning, and finally meta-learning (e.g.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p01] Association rule learning is a rule-based machine learning method for discovering relationships between variables in large databases.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p01] It is intended to identify strong rules discovered in databases using some measure of "interestingness".
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p01] Rule-based machine learning is a general term for any machine learning method that identifies, learns, or evolves "rules" to store, manipulate or apply knowledge.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p01] The defining characteristic of a rule-based machine learning algorithm is the identification and utilisation of a set of relational rules that collectively represent the knowledge captured by the system.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p01] This is in contrast to other machine learning algorithms that commonly identify a singular model that can be universally applied to any instance in order to make a prediction.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p01] Rule-based machine learning approaches include learning classifier systems, association rule learning, and artificial immune systems.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p01] Based on the concept of strong rules, Rakesh Agrawal, Tomasz Imieliński and Arun Swami introduced association rules for discovering regularities between products in large-scale transaction data recorded by point-of-sale (POS) systems in supermarkets.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p01] For example, the rule $\{\mathrm {onions,potatoes} \}\Rightarrow \{\mathrm {burger} \}$ found in the sales data of a supermarket would indicate that if a customer buys onions and potatoes together, they are likely to also buy hamburger meat.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p01] Such information can be used as the basis for decisions about marketing activities such as promotional pricing or product placements.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p01] In addition to market basket analysis, association rules are employed today in application areas including Web usage mining, intrusion detection, continuous production, and bioinformatics.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p01] In contrast with sequence mining, association rule learning typically does not consider the order of items either within a transaction or across transactions.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p01] Learning classifier systems (LCS) are a family of rule-based machine learning algorithms that combine a discovery component, typically a genetic algorithm, with a learning component, performing either supervised learning, reinforcement learning, or unsupervised learning.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p01] They seek to identify a set of context-dependent rules that collectively store and apply knowledge in a piecewise manner to make predictions.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p01] Inductive logic programming (ILP) is an approach to rule learning using logic programming as a uniform representation for input examples, background knowledge, and hypotheses.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p01] Given an encoding of the known background knowledge and a set of examples represented as a logical database of facts, an ILP system will derive a hypothesized logic program that entails all positive and no negative examples.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p01] Inductive programming is a related field that considers any kind of programming language for representing hypotheses (and not only logic programming), such as functional programs.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p01] Inductive logic programming is particularly useful in bioinformatics and natural language processing.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p01] Gordon Plotkin and Ehud Shapiro laid the initial theoretical foundation for inductive machine learning in a logical setting.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p01] Shapiro built their first implementation (Model Inference System) in 1981: a Prolog program that inductively inferred logic programs from positive and negative examples.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p01] The term *inductive* here refers to philosophical induction, suggesting a theory to explain observed facts, rather than mathematical induction, proving a property for all members of a well-ordered set.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p01] A **machine learning model** is a type of mathematical model that, once "trained" on a given dataset, can be used to make predictions or classifications on new data.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p01] During training, a learning algorithm iteratively adjusts the model's internal parameters to minimise errors in its predictions.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p01] By extension, the term "model" can refer to several levels of specificity, from a general class of models and their associated learning algorithms to a fully trained model with all its internal parameters tuned.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p01] Various types of models have been used and researched for machine learning systems, picking the best model for a task is called model selection.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p01] Artificial neural networks (ANNs), or connectionist systems, are computing systems vaguely inspired by the biological neural networks that constitute animal brains.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p01] Such systems "learn" to perform tasks by considering examples, generally without being programmed with any task-specific rules.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p01] An ANN is a model based on a collection of connected units or nodes called "artificial neurons", which loosely model the neurons in a biological brain.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p01] Each connection, like the synapses in a biological brain, can transmit information, a "signal", from one artificial neuron to another.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p01] An artificial neuron that receives a signal can process it and then signal additional artificial neurons connected to it.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p01] In common ANN implementations, the signal at a connection between artificial neurons is a real number, and the output of each artificial neuron is computed by some non-linear function of the sum of its inputs.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p01] The connections between artificial neurons are called "edges".
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p01] Artificial neurons and edges typically have a weight that adjusts as learning proceeds.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p01] The weight increases or decreases the strength of the signal at a connection.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p01] Artificial neurons may have a threshold such that the signal is only sent if the aggregate signal crosses that threshold.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p01] Typically, artificial neurons are aggregated into layers.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p01] Signals travel from the first layer (the input layer) to the last layer (the output layer), possibly after traversing the layers multiple times.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p01] The original goal of the ANN approach was to solve problems in the same way that a human brain would.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p01] However, over time, attention moved to performing specific tasks, leading to deviations from biology.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p01] Artificial neural networks have been used on a variety of tasks, including computer vision, speech recognition, machine translation, social network filtering, playing board and video games and medical diagnosis.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p01] Deep learning consists of multiple hidden layers in an artificial neural network.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p01] This approach tries to model the way the human brain processes light and sound into vision and hearing.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p01] Some successful applications of deep learning are computer vision and speech recognition.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p01] Decision tree learning uses a decision tree as a predictive model to go from observations about an item (represented in the branches) to conclusions about the item's target value (represented in the leaves).
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p01] It is one of the predictive modelling approaches used in statistics, data mining, and machine learning.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p01] Tree models where the target variable can take a discrete set of values are called classification trees; in these tree structures, leaves represent class labels, and branches represent conjunctions of features that lead to those class labels.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p01] Decision trees where the target variable can take continuous values (typically real numbers) are called regression trees.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p01] In decision analysis, a decision tree can be used to visually and explicitly represent decisions and decision making.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p01] In data mining, a decision tree describes data, but the resulting classification tree can be an input for decision-making.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p01] Random forest regression (RFR) falls under the umbrella of decision tree-based models.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p01] RFR is an ensemble learning method that builds multiple decision trees and averages their predictions to improve accuracy and to avoid overfitting.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p01] To build decision trees, RFR uses bootstrapped sampling; for instance, each decision tree is trained on random data from the training set.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p01] This random selection of RFR for training enables the model to reduce biased predictions and achieve a higher degree of accuracy.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p01] RFR generates independent decision trees, and it can work on single-output data as well as multiple regressor tasks.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p01] This makes RFR compatible to be use in various applications.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p01] Support-vector machines (SVMs), also known as support-vector networks, are a set of related supervised learning methods used for classification and regression.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p01] Given a set of training examples, each marked as belonging to one of two categories, an SVM training algorithm builds a model that predicts whether a new example falls into one category.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p01] An SVM training algorithm is a non-probabilistic, binary, linear classifier, although methods such as Platt scaling exist to use SVM in a probabilistic classification setting.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p01] In addition to performing linear classification, SVMs can efficiently perform a non-linear classification using what is called the kernel trick, implicitly mapping their inputs into high-dimensional feature spaces.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p01] Regression analysis encompasses a large variety of statistical methods to estimate the relationship between input variables and their associated features.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p01] Its most common form is linear regression, where a single line is drawn to best fit the given data according to a mathematical criterion such as ordinary least squares.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p01] The latter is often extended by regularisation methods to mitigate overfitting and bias, as in ridge regression.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p01] Multivariate linear regression extends the concept of linear regression to handle multiple dependent variables simultaneously.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p01] This approach estimates the relationships between a set of input variables and several output variables by fitting a multidimensional linear model.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p01] It is particularly useful in scenarios where outputs are interdependent or share underlying patterns, such as predicting multiple economic indicators or reconstructing images, which are inherently multi-dimensional.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p01] A Bayesian network, belief network, or directed acyclic graphical model is a probabilistic graphical model that represents a set of random variables and their conditional independence with a directed acyclic graph (DAG).
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p01] For example, a Bayesian network could represent the probabilistic relationships between diseases and symptoms.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p01] Given symptoms, the network can be used to compute the probabilities of the presence of various diseases.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p01] Efficient algorithms exist that perform inference and learning.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p01] Bayesian networks that model sequences of variables, like speech signals or protein sequences, are called dynamic Bayesian networks.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p01] Generalisations of Bayesian networks that can represent and solve decision problems under uncertainty are called influence diagrams.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p01] A Gaussian process is a stochastic process in which every finite collection of the random variables in the process has a multivariate normal distribution, and it relies on a pre-defined covariance function, or kernel, that models how pairs of points relate to each other depending on their locations.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p01] Given a set of observed points, or input–output examples, the distribution of the (unobserved) output of a new point as a function of its input data can be directly computed by looking at the observed points and the covariances between those points and the new, unobserved point.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p01] Gaussian processes are popular surrogate models in Bayesian optimisation used to do hyperparameter optimisation.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p01] A genetic algorithm (GA) is a search algorithm and heuristic technique that mimics the process of natural selection, using methods such as mutation and crossover to generate new genotypes in the hope of finding good solutions to a given problem.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p01] In machine learning, genetic algorithms were used in the 1980s and 1990s.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p01] Conversely, machine learning techniques have been used to improve the performance of genetic and evolutionary algorithms.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p01] The theory of belief functions, also referred to as evidence theory or Dempster–Shafer theory, is a general framework for reasoning with uncertainty, with understood connections to other frameworks such as probability, possibility and imprecise probability theories.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p01] These theoretical frameworks can be thought of as a kind of learner and have some analogous properties of how evidence is combined (e.g., Dempster's rule of combination), just like how in a pmf-based Bayesian approach would combine probabilities.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p01] However, there are many caveats to these beliefs functions when compared to Bayesian approaches to incorporate ignorance and uncertainty quantification.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p01] However, the computational complexity of these algorithms is dependent on the number of propositions (classes), and can lead to a much higher computation time when compared to other machine learning approaches.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p01] Rule-based machine learning (RBML) is a branch of machine learning that automatically discovers and learns 'rules' from data.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p01] It provides interpretable models, making it useful for decision-making in fields like healthcare, fraud detection, and cybersecurity.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p01] Key RBML techniques includes learning classifier systems, association rule learning, artificial immune systems, and other similar models.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p01] These methods extract patterns from data and evolve rules over time.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p01] Typically, machine learning models require a high quantity of reliable data to perform accurate predictions.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p01] When training a machine learning model, machine learning engineers need to target and collect a large and representative sample of data.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p01] Data from the training set can be as varied as a corpus of text, a collection of images, sensor data, and data collected from individual users of a service.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p01] Overfitting is something to watch out for when training a machine learning model.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p01] Trained models derived from biased or non-evaluated data can result in skewed or undesired predictions.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p01] Biased models may result in detrimental outcomes, thereby furthering the negative impacts on society or objectives.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p01] Algorithmic bias is a potential result of data not being fully prepared for training.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p01] Machine learning ethics is becoming a field of study and, notably, becoming integrated within machine learning engineering teams.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p01] Federated learning is an adapted form of distributed artificial intelligence to train machine learning models that decentralises the training process, allowing for users' privacy to be maintained by not needing to send their data to a centralised server.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p01] This also increases efficiency by decentralising the training process to many devices.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p01] For example, Gboard uses federated machine learning to train search query prediction models on users' mobile phones without having to send individual searches back to Google.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p01] In 2006, the media-services provider Netflix held the first "Netflix Prize" competition to find a program to better predict user preferences and improve the accuracy of its existing Cinematch movie recommendation algorithm by at least 10%.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p01] A joint team made up of researchers from AT&T Labs-Research in collaboration with the teams Big Chaos and Pragmatic Theory built an ensemble model to win the Grand Prize in 2009 for $1 million.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p01] Shortly after the prize was awarded, Netflix realised that viewers' ratings were not the best indicators of their viewing patterns ("everything is a recommendation") and they changed their recommendation engine accordingly.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p01] In 2010, an article in *The Wall Street Journal* noted the use of machine learning by Rebellion Research to predict the 2008 financial crisis.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p01] In 2012, co-founder of Sun Microsystems, Vinod Khosla, predicted that 80% of medical doctors jobs would be lost in the next two decades to automated machine learning medical diagnostic software.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p01] In 2014, it was reported that a machine learning algorithm had been applied in the field of art history to study fine art paintings and that it may have revealed previously unrecognised influences among artists.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p01] In 2019 Springer Nature published the first research book created using machine learning.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p01] In 2020, machine learning technology was used to help make diagnoses and aid researchers in developing a cure for COVID-19.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p01] Machine learning was recently applied to predict the pro-environmental behaviour of travellers.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p01] Recently, machine learning technology was also applied to optimise smartphone's performance and thermal behaviour based on the user's interaction with the phone.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p01] When applied correctly, machine learning algorithms (MLAs) can utilise a wide range of company characteristics to predict stock returns without overfitting.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p01] By employing effective feature engineering and combining forecasts, MLAs can generate results that far surpass those obtained from basic linear techniques like OLS.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p01] Recent advancements in machine learning have extended into the field of quantum chemistry, where novel algorithms now enable the prediction of solvent effects on chemical reactions, thereby offering new tools for chemists to tailor experimental conditions for optimal outcomes.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p01] Machine Learning is becoming a useful tool to investigate and predict evacuation decision-making in large-scale and small-scale disasters.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p01] Different solutions have been tested to predict if and when householders decide to evacuate during wildfires and hurricanes.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p01] Other applications have been focusing on pre evacuation decisions in building fires.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p02] Although machine learning has been transformative in some fields, machine-learning programs often fail to deliver expected results.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p02] Reasons for this are numerous: lack of (suitable) data, lack of access to the data, data bias, privacy problems, badly chosen tasks and algorithms, wrong tools and people, lack of resources, and evaluation problems.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p02] The "black box theory" poses another yet significant challenge.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p02] Black box refers to a situation where the algorithm producing an output is entirely opaque, meaning that even the designers of an application cannot audit the pattern that the machine extracted from the data.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p02] The House of Lords Select Committee, which claimed that such an "intelligence system" that could have a "substantial impact on an individual's life" would not be considered acceptable unless it provided "a full and satisfactory explanation for the decisions" it makes.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p02] In 2018, a self-driving car from Uber failed to detect a pedestrian, who was killed after a collision.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p02] Attempts to use machine learning in healthcare with the IBM Watson system failed to deliver even after years of time and billions of dollars invested.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p02] Microsoft's Bing Chat chatbot has been reported to produce hostile and offensive response against its users.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p02] Machine learning has been used as a strategy to update the evidence related to a systematic review and increased reviewer burden related to the growth of biomedical literature.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p02] While it has improved with training sets, it has not yet developed sufficiently to reduce the workload burden without limiting the necessary sensitivity for the findings research itself.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p02] Explainable AI (XAI), or Interpretable AI, or Explainable Machine Learning (XML), is artificial intelligence (AI) in which humans can understand the decisions or predictions made by the AI.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p02] It contrasts with the "black box" concept in machine learning where even its designers cannot explain why an AI arrived at a specific decision.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p02] By refining the mental models of users of AI-powered systems and dismantling their misconceptions, XAI promises to help users perform more effectively.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p02] XAI may be an implementation of the social right to explanation.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p02] Settling on a bad, overly complex theory gerrymandered to fit all the past training data is known as overfitting.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p02] Many systems attempt to reduce overfitting by rewarding a theory in accordance with how well it fits the data but penalising the theory in accordance with how complex the theory is.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p02] It is unclear to what extent the phenomenon threatens the long-term development of such models, and some techniques have been proposed to mitigate the effect.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p02] , inconsistent carriage lengths, unnatural amounts of visual noise, and a carriage bending along its length as it rounds the turn.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p02] In the field of artificial intelligence (AI), a hallucination or artificial hallucination (also called bullshitting, confabulation, or delusion) is a response generated by AI that contains false or misleading information presented as fact.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p02] The term draws a loose analogy with human psychology, where a hallucination typically involves false *percepts*.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p02] For example, a chatbot powered by large language models (LLMs), like ChatGPT, may embed plausible-sounding random falsehoods within its generated content.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p02] Detecting and mitigating errors and hallucinations pose significant challenges for practical deployment and reliability of LLMs in high-stakes scenarios, such as chip design, supply chain logistics, and medical diagnostics.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p02] Some software engineers and statisticians have criticized the specific term "AI hallucination" for unreasonably anthropomorphizing computers.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p02] Symbolic artificial intelligence models generally do not produce hallucinations, unlike large language models.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p02] Learners can also be disappointed by "learning the wrong lesson".
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p02] A toy example is that an image classifier trained only on pictures of brown horses and black cats might conclude that all brown patches are likely to be horses.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p02] Modifying these patterns on a legitimate image can result in "adversarial" images that the system misclassifies.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p02] Adversarial vulnerabilities can also result in nonlinear systems or from non-pattern perturbations.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p02] For some systems, it is possible to change the output by only changing a single adversarially chosen pixel.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p02] Machine learning models are often vulnerable to manipulation or evasion via adversarial machine learning.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p02] Researchers have demonstrated how backdoors can be placed undetectably into classifying (e.g., for categories "spam" and "not spam" of posts) machine learning models that are often developed or trained by third parties.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p02] Parties can change the classification of any input, including in cases for which a type of data/software transparency is provided, possibly including white-box access.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p02] Classification of machine learning models can be validated by accuracy estimation techniques like the holdout method, which splits the data into a training and test set (conventionally 2/3 training set and 1/3 test set designation) and evaluates the performance of the training model on the test set.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p02] In comparison, the K-fold-cross-validation method randomly partitions the data into K subsets and then K experiments are performed each considering 1 subset for evaluation and the remaining K-1 subsets for training the model.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p02] In addition to the holdout and cross-validation methods, bootstrap, which samples n instances with replacement from the dataset, can be used to assess model accuracy.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p02] In addition to overall accuracy, investigators frequently report sensitivity and specificity, meaning true positive rate (TPR) and true negative rate (TNR), respectively.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p02] Similarly, investigators sometimes report the false positive rate (FPR) as well as the false negative rate (FNR).
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p02] However, these rates are ratios that fail to reveal their numerators and denominators.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p02] Receiver operating characteristic (ROC), along with the accompanying Area Under the ROC Curve (AUC), offer additional tools for classification model assessment.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p02] Higher AUC is associated with a better performing model.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p02] The ethics of artificial intelligence covers a broad range of topics within AI that are considered to have particular ethical stakes.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p02] This includes algorithmic biases, fairness, accountability, transparency, privacy, and regulation, particularly where systems influence or automate human decision-making.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p02] Some application areas may also have particularly important ethical implications, like healthcare, education, criminal justice, or the military.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p02] Different machine learning approaches can suffer from different data biases.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p02] A machine learning system trained specifically on current customers may not be able to predict the needs of new customer groups that are not represented in the training data.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p02] When trained on human-made data, machine learning is likely to pick up the constitutional and unconscious biases already present in society.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p02] Systems that are trained on datasets collected with biases may exhibit these biases upon use (algorithmic bias), thus digitising cultural prejudices.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p02] For example, in 1988, the UK's Commission for Racial Equality found that St.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p02] George's Medical School had been using a computer program trained from data of previous admissions staff and this program had denied nearly 60 candidates who were found to either be women or have non-European-sounding names.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p02] Using job hiring data from a firm with racist hiring policies may lead to a machine learning system duplicating the bias by scoring job applicants by similarity to previous successful applicants.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p02] Another example includes predictive policing company Geolitica's predictive algorithm that resulted in "disproportionately high levels of over-policing in low-income and minority communities" after being trained with historical crime data.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p02] In fact, according to research carried out by the Computing Research Association in 2021, "female faculty make up just 16.1%" of all faculty members who focus on AI among several universities around the world.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p02] Furthermore, among the group of "new U.S. resident AI PhD graduates," 45% identified as white, 22.4% as Asian, 3.2% as Hispanic, and 2.4% as African American, which further demonstrates a lack of diversity in the field of AI.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p02] Language models learned from data have been shown to contain human-like biases.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p02] Because human languages contain biases, machines trained on language *corpora* will necessarily also learn these biases.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p02] In 2016, Microsoft tested Tay, a chatbot that learned from Twitter, and it quickly picked up racist and sexist language.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p02] In an experiment carried out by ProPublica, an investigative journalism organisation, a machine learning algorithm's insight into the recidivism rates among prisoners falsely flagged "black defendants high risk twice as often as white defendants".
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p02] In 2015, Google Photos once tagged a couple of black people as gorillas, which caused controversy.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p02] The gorilla label was subsequently removed, and in 2023, it still cannot recognise gorillas.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p02] Similar issues with recognising non-white people have been found in many other systems.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p02] Because of such challenges, the effective use of machine learning may take longer to be adopted in other domains.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p02] Concern for fairness in machine learning, that is, reducing bias in machine learning and propelling its use for human good, is increasingly expressed by artificial intelligence scientists, including Fei-Fei Li, who said that "[t]here's nothing artificial about AI.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p02] It's inspired by people, it's created by people, and—most importantly—it impacts people.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p02] There are concerns among health care professionals that these systems might not be designed in the public's interest but as income-generating machines.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p02] This is especially true in the United States, where there is a long-standing ethical dilemma of improving health care, but also increasing profits.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p02] For example, the algorithms could be designed to provide patients with unnecessary tests or medication in which the algorithm's proprietary owners hold stakes.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p02] There is potential for machine learning in health care to provide professionals with an additional tool to diagnose, medicate, and plan recovery paths for patients, but this requires these biases to be mitigated.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p02] Since the 2010s, advances in both machine learning algorithms and computer hardware have led to more efficient methods for training deep neural networks (a particular narrow subdomain of machine learning) that contain many layers of nonlinear hidden units.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p02] By 2019, graphics processing units (GPUs), often with AI-specific enhancements, had displaced CPUs as the dominant method of training large-scale commercial cloud AI.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p02] OpenAI estimated the hardware compute used in the largest deep learning projects from AlexNet (2012) to AlphaZero (2017), and found a 300,000-fold increase in the amount of compute required, with a doubling-time trendline of 3.4 months.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p02] Tensor Processing Units (TPUs) are specialised hardware accelerators developed by Google specifically for machine learning workloads.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p02] Unlike general-purpose GPUs and FPGAs, TPUs are optimised for tensor computations, making them particularly efficient for deep learning tasks such as training and inference.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p02] They are widely used in Google Cloud AI services and large-scale machine learning models like Google's DeepMind AlphaFold and large language models.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p02] TPUs leverage matrix multiplication units and high-bandwidth memory to accelerate computations while maintaining energy efficiency.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p02] Since their introduction in 2016, TPUs have become a key component of AI infrastructure, especially in cloud-based environments.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p02] Neuromorphic computing refers to a class of computing systems designed to emulate the structure and functionality of biological neural networks.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p02] These systems may be implemented through software-based simulations on conventional hardware or through specialised hardware architectures.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p02] A physical neural network is a specific type of neuromorphic hardware that relies on electrically adjustable materials, such as memristors, to emulate the function of neural synapses.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p02] The term "physical neural network" highlights the use of physical hardware for computation, as opposed to software-based implementations.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p02] It broadly refers to artificial neural networks that use materials with adjustable resistance to replicate neural synapses.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p02] Embedded machine learning is a sub-field of machine learning where models are deployed on embedded systems with limited computing resources, such as wearable computers, edge devices and microcontrollers.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p02] Running models directly on these devices eliminates the need to transfer and store data on cloud servers for further processing, thereby reducing the risk of data breaches, privacy leaks and theft of intellectual property, personal data and business secrets.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p02] Embedded machine learning can be achieved through various techniques, such as hardware acceleration, approximate computing, and model optimization.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/machine-learning-p02] Common optimization techniques include pruning, quantisation, knowledge distillation, low-rank factorisation, network architecture search, and parameter sharing.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/software-deployment] Deployment can involve activities on the producer (software developer) side or on the consumer (user) side or both.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/software-deployment] Deployment to consumers is a hard task because the target systems are diverse and unpredictable.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/software-deployment] Software as a service avoids these difficulties by deploying only to dedicated servers that are typically under the producer's control.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/software-deployment] Because every software system is unique, the precise processes or procedures within each activity can hardly be defined.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/software-deployment] Therefore, "deployment" should be interpreted as a *general process* that has to be customized according to specific requirements or characteristics.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/software-deployment] When computers were extremely large, expensive, and bulky (mainframes and minicomputers), the software was often bundled together with the hardware by manufacturers and provided for free.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/software-deployment] A pivotal moment occurred in 1969 when IBM, influenced by antitrust lawsuits, began charging for software and services separately from hardware.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/software-deployment] This "unbundling" effectively created the modern software industry, turning software into a commercial product.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/software-deployment] Early deployment processes were highly structured; the Lincoln Labs Phased Model, developed in 1956 for the SAGE air defense system, introduced sequential phases that influenced later methodologies.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/software-deployment] This approach was formalized in the waterfall model, which became dominant after being described by Winston Royce in 1970.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/software-deployment] It led to infrequent, costly, and lengthy release cycles, often taking years.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/software-deployment] If business software needed to be installed, it often required an expensive, time-consuming visit by a systems architect or a consultant.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/software-deployment] For complex, on-premises installation of enterprise software today, this is sometimes still the case.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/software-deployment] The development of mass-market software for the new age of microcomputers in the 1980s brought new forms of software distribution – first cartridges, then Compact Cassettes, then floppy disks, and later (in the 1990s and beyond) optical media, the internet and flash drives.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/software-deployment] This shift meant that software deployment could be left to the customer.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/software-deployment] During this period, alternatives to the rigid waterfall model emerged.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/software-deployment] The Spiral Model, proposed by Barry Boehm in 1988, introduced a risk-driven, iterative approach that challenged waterfall's linear structure and paved the way for more flexible, agile methodologies.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/software-deployment] As customer-led deployment became standard, it was recognized that configuration should be user-friendly.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/software-deployment] In the 1990s, tools like InstallShield became popular, providing installer wizards that eliminated the need for users to perform complex tasks like editing registry entries.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/software-deployment] In pre-internet software deployments, releases were by nature expensive and infrequent affairs.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/software-deployment] The spread of the internet fundamentally transformed software distribution and made end-to-end agile software development viable by enabling rapid collaboration and digital delivery.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/software-deployment] The foundations for modern rapid deployment were laid in the 1990s when Kent Beck developed Continuous Integration as a core practice of Extreme Programming, advocating for developers to integrate their work daily.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/software-deployment] The advent of cloud computing and software as a service (SaaS) in the 2000s further accelerated this trend, allowing software to be deployed to a large number of customers in minutes.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/software-deployment] This shift also meant deployment schedules were now typically determined by the software supplier, not the customers.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/software-deployment] Such flexibility led to the rise of continuous delivery as a viable option, especially for web applications.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/software-deployment] Modern deployment strategies that build upon these principles include blue–green deployment and canary release deployment.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/software-deployment] process and is sometimes classified as part of the development process rather than deployment process.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/software-deployment] and transfer to the computer system(s) on which it will be run in production.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/software-deployment] required for the system to operate with tolerable performance and planning and/or documenting subsequent activities of the deployment process.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/software-deployment] for executing the software (manually or automatically).
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/software-deployment] and/or making all the required subsystems ready to use.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/software-deployment] , the main copy of the software to be used by users - "production" - might be installed on a production server in a production environment.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/software-deployment] ), or even be gradually rolled out in parallel to different groups of customers, with the possibility of canceling one or more of the parallel deployments.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/software-deployment] Deactivation is the inverse of activation and refers to shutting down any already-executing components of a system.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/software-deployment] Deactivation is often required to perform other deployment activities, e.g., a software system may need to be deactivated before an update can be performed.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/software-deployment] Uninstallation is the inverse of installation.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/software-deployment] It is the removal of a system that is no longer required.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/software-deployment] The update process replaces an earlier version of all or part of a software system with a newer release.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/software-deployment] It commonly consists of deactivation followed by installation.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/software-deployment] , the old version of a software application is typically also uninstalled as an automatic part of the process.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/software-deployment] Automation of these update processes ranges from fully automatic to user-initiated and controlled.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/software-deployment] is an example of a system with a semi-automatic method for retrieving and installing updates to both the antivirus definitions and other components of the system.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/software-deployment] Other software products provide query mechanisms for determining when updates are available.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/software-deployment] Version tracking systems help the user find and install updates to software systems.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/software-deployment] For example: The Software Catalog stores the version and other information for each software package installed on a local system.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/software-deployment] One-click of a button launches a browser window to the upgrade web page for the application, including auto-filling of the user name and password for sites that require a login.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/software-deployment] so the process can be configured to be fully automated.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/software-deployment] Some third-party software also supports automated version tracking and upgrading for certain Windows software packages.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/software-deployment] The complexity and variability of software products have fostered the emergence of specialized roles for coordinating and engineering the deployment process.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/software-deployment] For desktop systems, end-users frequently also become the "software deployers" when they install a software package on their machine.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/software-deployment] The deployment of enterprise software involves many more roles, and those roles typically change as the application progresses from the test (pre-production) to production environments.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/transfer-learning] Since transfer learning makes use of training with multiple objective functions it is related to cost-sensitive machine learning and multi-objective optimization.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/transfer-learning] In 1976, Bozinovski and Fulgosi published a paper addressing transfer learning in neural network training.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/transfer-learning] The paper gives a mathematical and geometrical model of the topic.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/transfer-learning] In 1981, a report considered the application of transfer learning to a dataset of images representing letters of computer terminals, experimentally demonstrating positive and negative transfer learning.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/transfer-learning] In 1992, Lorien Pratt formulated the discriminability-based transfer (DBT) algorithm.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/transfer-learning] By 1998, the field had advanced to include multi-task learning, along with more formal theoretical foundations.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/transfer-learning] Influential publications on transfer learning include the book *Learning to Learn* in 1998, a 2009 survey and a 2019 survey.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/transfer-learning] Ng said in his NIPS 2016 tutorial that TL would become the next driver of machine learning commercial success after supervised learning.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/transfer-learning] In the 2020 paper, "Rethinking Pre-Training and self-training", Zoph et al. reported that pre-training can hurt accuracy, and advocate self-training instead.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/transfer-learning] The definition of transfer learning is given in terms of domains and tasks.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/transfer-learning] A domain ${\mathcal {D}}$ consists of: a feature space ${\mathcal {X}}$ and a marginal probability distribution $P(X)$ , where $X=\{x_{1},...,x_{n}\}\in {\mathcal {X}}$ .
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/transfer-learning] Given a specific domain, ${\mathcal {D}}=\{{\mathcal {X}},P(X)\}$ , a task consists of two components: a label space ${\mathcal {Y}}$ and an objective predictive function $f:{\mathcal {X}}\rightarrow {\mathcal {Y}}$ .
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/transfer-learning] The function f is used to predict the corresponding label $f(x)$ of a new instance x .
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/transfer-learning] Algorithms for transfer learning are available in Markov logic networks and Bayesian networks.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/transfer-learning] Transfer learning has been applied to cancer subtype discovery, building utilization, general game playing, text classification, digit recognition, medical imaging and spam filtering.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/transfer-learning] It was noted that this relationship worked in both directions, showing that EEG brainwaves can likewise be used to classify EMG signals.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/transfer-learning] The experiments noted that the accuracy of neural networks and convolutional neural networks were improved through transfer learning both prior to any learning (compared to standard random weight distribution) and at the end of the learning process (asymptote).
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/transfer-learning] That is, results are improved by exposure to another domain.
[src:gcp-vertex-ai/transfer-learning] Moreover, the end-user of a pre-trained model can change the structure of fully-connected layers to improve performance.
